WEBVTT

00:02.043 --> 00:03.586
[TV static drones]

00:03.670 --> 00:05.964
[bright tone]

00:09.217 --> 00:12.220
[sheep bleating]

00:14.848 --> 00:17.767
[spirited orchestral music]

00:17.851 --> 00:19.436
- Hyah, hyah!

00:19.519 --> 00:24.357
♪ ♪

00:24.441 --> 00:26.025
- Hup, hup!

00:48.757 --> 00:54.179
♪ ♪

00:54.262 --> 00:56.181
- Hup, hup.

00:56.264 --> 01:02.979
♪ ♪

01:03.062 --> 01:04.939
[horse whinnies]

01:05.023 --> 01:06.357
- Come on. Hyah.

01:09.486 --> 01:12.447
Come on, come on.

01:12.530 --> 01:14.616
- Take those packages to--
- Whoa.

01:14.699 --> 01:15.950
- Careful with those.
They're fragile.

01:16.034 --> 01:17.035
- Go slow!

01:17.118 --> 01:19.287
- Give that to Mr. Prue.
- This way, this way.

01:19.370 --> 01:22.207
- Hoisting it up!
- Careful, careful!

01:23.208 --> 01:26.878
- Okay!
- Let's go! Let's go!

01:26.961 --> 01:33.927
♪ ♪

01:39.265 --> 01:42.560
[indistinct shouting]

01:42.644 --> 01:45.647
[dog barking]

01:57.075 --> 01:58.993
- We're gonna go back
for another load!

01:59.077 --> 02:02.080
[indistinct shouting]

02:06.417 --> 02:08.044
- Morning, Mr. Griffin.

02:08.127 --> 02:09.546
They're moving in
at last, then.

02:09.629 --> 02:13.299
- Looks like it.
- Ah, bad news, I'm afraid.

02:13.383 --> 02:15.760
- They're old.
They get bad news every week.

02:15.844 --> 02:17.178
- You're all heart.
- I got it!

02:17.262 --> 02:18.429
I got it!

02:18.513 --> 02:25.478
♪ ♪

02:38.867 --> 02:41.369
- Looks like another one.
- Oh, dear.

02:41.452 --> 02:43.580
I wonder who that is now.

02:43.663 --> 02:45.415
- I'll take those.
Thank you, John.

02:45.498 --> 02:47.917
- Why not let Miss Armstrong
carry them up?

02:48.001 --> 02:49.252
Or that one at least.

02:49.335 --> 02:50.420
- Thank you, Mrs. Bauer,

02:50.503 --> 02:52.046
but I think I know
what I'm doing.

02:52.130 --> 02:59.095
♪ ♪

03:01.514 --> 03:02.765
- I'm afraid none of them

03:02.849 --> 03:04.934
are worth the paper
they're printed on.

03:05.018 --> 03:08.897
- But surely with the railroad
spreading all over the country.

03:08.980 --> 03:10.857
Every day, the papers talk
of some new millionaire

03:10.940 --> 03:12.483
who's made his fortune
out of railways.

03:12.567 --> 03:14.152
- And every day,
the bankruptcy courts

03:14.235 --> 03:16.070
see rail companies go under,

03:16.154 --> 03:18.489
taking their owners
and investors down with them.

03:20.283 --> 03:23.077
Miss Brook, the plain fact is,

03:23.161 --> 03:25.121
I've looked into the estate
of the late Mr. Brook.

03:25.204 --> 03:26.706
- The late General Brook.

03:27.999 --> 03:31.628
- The late General Brook,
and I cannot find any assets

03:31.711 --> 03:33.671
beyond the contents
of his bank account.

03:33.755 --> 03:34.839
- And the house.

03:34.923 --> 03:37.133
- The house is rented,
Miss Brook.

03:37.216 --> 03:39.135
- I'm sure that's wrong.

03:39.218 --> 03:41.971
- No, I'm afraid not.

03:42.055 --> 03:43.932
- But my father always said--

03:49.228 --> 03:52.106
I see.

03:52.190 --> 03:53.650
So how much is left?

03:53.733 --> 03:56.653
- I've paid the funeral charges
and other outstanding accounts,

03:56.736 --> 03:57.946
and I will waive my own fee.

03:58.029 --> 03:59.989
- There's no need.
- There is every need.

04:00.073 --> 04:01.783
You will have
in your possession

04:01.866 --> 04:04.369
somewhere in the region of $30.

04:08.206 --> 04:09.707
- You see, Mr. Raikes,
none of this

04:09.791 --> 04:11.793
is what my father told me.

04:11.876 --> 04:12.919
- So I gathered.

04:16.089 --> 04:19.842
What are you going to do?
- I'm not sure.

04:19.926 --> 04:22.011
- You mentioned your father's
sisters in New York.

04:22.095 --> 04:23.680
- My aunts
were not on good terms

04:23.763 --> 04:25.515
with my father, Mr. Raikes.

04:25.598 --> 04:27.558
They disliked him,
and he disliked them,

04:27.642 --> 04:30.311
so they have played
no part in my life.

04:30.395 --> 04:33.147
- I would only ask you
to consider your options,

04:33.231 --> 04:35.900
realistically.

04:35.984 --> 04:38.361
- You mean
beggars can't be choosers?

04:38.444 --> 04:41.322
[plucky orchestral music]

04:41.406 --> 04:43.658
- Well, the rent is paid
to the end of the month.

04:43.741 --> 04:45.118
Perhaps you will signal
your intentions

04:45.201 --> 04:47.120
before that point is reached?

04:47.203 --> 04:50.873
- Perhaps I will.
Thank you.

04:50.957 --> 04:56.170
♪ ♪

04:56.254 --> 04:59.048
- I'm sorry
I couldn't be more help.

04:59.132 --> 05:02.093
- Don't worry, Mr. Raikes,
I'm not beaten yet.

05:02.176 --> 05:03.553
- At the risk of impertinence,
I would say

05:03.636 --> 05:05.805
you're a long way
from being beaten, Miss Brook.

05:14.439 --> 05:17.400
[soft dramatic music]

05:17.483 --> 05:24.449
♪ ♪

05:27.368 --> 05:30.329
- [breathes sharply]

05:45.053 --> 05:46.387
- What does she say?

05:46.471 --> 05:48.097
- She thanks you
for the letter

05:48.181 --> 05:49.724
that you did not show me

05:49.807 --> 05:51.601
and for the tickets
that you purchased

05:51.684 --> 05:53.603
without my knowledge.

05:53.686 --> 05:54.937
She means to join us here

05:55.021 --> 05:56.606
just as soon
as she has closed the house

05:56.689 --> 05:58.107
and sold her furniture.

05:58.191 --> 06:00.943
- Oh, what a relief.
- A relief?

06:01.027 --> 06:02.904
And who is to support her?

06:02.987 --> 06:05.239
Exactly. Me.

06:05.323 --> 06:06.407
With the Van Rhijn money,

06:06.491 --> 06:08.951
which was not achieved
at no cost to myself.

06:09.035 --> 06:09.952
You were allowed

06:10.036 --> 06:11.913
the pure and tranquil life
of a spinster.

06:11.996 --> 06:13.081
I was not.

06:13.164 --> 06:15.416
- I'm very grateful.
- So you should be.

06:15.500 --> 06:17.794
- Well, I'm glad she's coming.
- [sighs]

06:17.877 --> 06:19.962
- And if my letter
played a part in her decision,

06:20.046 --> 06:21.464
then I'm glad I sent it.

06:21.547 --> 06:22.799
- I doubt it was your letter.

06:22.882 --> 06:25.343
More likely, she has discovered
her father left her

06:25.426 --> 06:27.220
without a penny to her name.

06:27.303 --> 06:30.181
Henry couldn't provide
for a dog in a ditch.

06:30.264 --> 06:31.849
He never kept a dollar
in his pocket

06:31.933 --> 06:34.310
if there were women or drink
within 500 miles.

06:34.393 --> 06:37.021
- Agnes, our brother has died.

06:37.105 --> 06:38.272
- Our brother with whom

06:38.356 --> 06:40.441
we have had no connection
these many years.

06:40.525 --> 06:42.360
- We should have gone
for the funeral anyway.

06:42.443 --> 06:44.904
- It wasn't worth
an uncomfortable day of travel

06:44.987 --> 06:47.657
to make sure Henry was dead.

06:47.740 --> 06:49.117
- At least
there's a railway station

06:49.200 --> 06:51.953
in Doylestown now,
unlike in our day,

06:52.036 --> 06:53.204
but she'll need to get up early

06:53.287 --> 06:55.331
to catch the first train
to Lansdale,

06:55.414 --> 06:57.458
and then she'll have to change
at Bethlehem

06:57.542 --> 06:59.293
and take
the Lehigh Valley Railroad

06:59.377 --> 07:01.587
to Exchange Place
in Jersey City,

07:01.671 --> 07:03.631
and then catch the ferry
across the Hudson

07:03.714 --> 07:05.341
to Desbrosses Street.

07:05.424 --> 07:07.260
From there, she could take
an elevated train--

07:07.343 --> 07:09.971
- Are you planning
to open a travel business?

07:10.054 --> 07:11.222
- No.

07:11.305 --> 07:13.641
- Then what on Earth makes you
think I would be interested?

07:13.724 --> 07:14.851
- [sighs]

07:14.934 --> 07:18.062
I only meant
it's a long journey, Agnes.

07:18.146 --> 07:19.480
12 hours or more.

07:19.564 --> 07:20.648
- And what are we
to do with her

07:20.731 --> 07:23.776
now that she's on her way
to disturb our peace?

07:23.860 --> 07:25.528
- Perhaps she'd like to work.

07:25.611 --> 07:28.156
If her father
has left her penniless,

07:28.239 --> 07:30.158
maybe she could be a governess.

07:30.241 --> 07:34.162
- A niece of mine a governess?
- She's my niece too.

07:34.245 --> 07:36.122
- I've not noticed
you volunteering

07:36.205 --> 07:38.040
to make a contribution
to the household

07:38.124 --> 07:40.251
as a governess.

07:40.334 --> 07:42.795
- We are
her only living relatives.

07:42.879 --> 07:44.839
We owe her the duty of care.

07:44.922 --> 07:47.466
- We do not owe her anything.

07:47.550 --> 07:51.053
Her father robbed us
of all that we possessed.

07:51.137 --> 07:52.221
Look at this.

07:52.305 --> 07:54.432
Invitations, charity appeals,

07:54.515 --> 07:58.102
questions from bankers
and brokers.

07:58.186 --> 08:01.022
When am I expected
to answer them all?

08:01.105 --> 08:02.648
It's not fair.

08:02.732 --> 08:09.238
♪ ♪

08:09.322 --> 08:10.865
Is it that woman again?

08:10.948 --> 08:12.992
- You must be pleased
they're moving in

08:13.075 --> 08:14.911
and we have peace at last.

08:14.994 --> 08:18.164
- I don't know which is worse,
the noise of the builders,

08:18.247 --> 08:20.958
or the chance of running
into her in the street.

08:21.042 --> 08:23.669
[spirited orchestral music]

08:23.753 --> 08:27.590
- Good afternoon, Mrs. Russell.
- Mr. White.

08:27.673 --> 08:29.425
- You've never seen it
without scaffolding.

08:29.508 --> 08:32.220
- It's everything you promised.

08:32.303 --> 08:33.262
- Steady on!

08:36.015 --> 08:37.516
- Mrs. Russell, Mr. White.

08:37.600 --> 08:39.227
[indistinct chatter]

08:39.310 --> 08:40.978
- [gasps]
Oh.

08:41.062 --> 08:48.027
♪ ♪

08:50.321 --> 08:52.448
- I'm pleased with the size.

08:52.531 --> 08:54.992
Big enough to be splendid
without being oppressively so.

08:55.076 --> 08:56.077
- I agree.

08:56.160 --> 08:57.620
One needs
to be able to breathe.

08:57.703 --> 09:00.957
♪ ♪

09:01.040 --> 09:02.917
Why is he
bringing that downstairs?

09:03.000 --> 09:04.418
- I want to try
and put the other Boucher

09:04.502 --> 09:06.087
in the drawing room.

09:06.170 --> 09:08.130
[indistinct chatter]

09:11.676 --> 09:13.135
- Is that from the gallery?

09:15.346 --> 09:17.181
- Is that
from the Palazzo Borghese?

09:17.265 --> 09:20.726
- No, the Hôtel de Soubise
in the Marais.

09:20.810 --> 09:22.979
You're thinking of the clock
in the library.

09:23.062 --> 09:29.986
♪ ♪

09:31.779 --> 09:34.115
- Another inch.
- As you wish, Mrs. Russell.

09:36.200 --> 09:37.785
- The carpets work well
in here, I think.

09:37.868 --> 09:39.120
- I wasn't convinced
they'd go together,

09:39.203 --> 09:40.246
but they do.

09:40.329 --> 09:47.086
♪ ♪

09:54.260 --> 09:55.594
I wish you wouldn't
do that in here.

09:55.678 --> 09:59.056
What is the smoking room for?
- To entertain my friends.

09:59.140 --> 10:01.642
And I will not be told
what I can and can't do

10:01.726 --> 10:03.686
in my own library.

10:03.769 --> 10:05.479
- The windows can be opened
when you go to change.

10:05.563 --> 10:07.898
I'll ask Mrs. Bruce.
- Hm?

10:07.982 --> 10:09.650
- The new housekeeper.

10:09.734 --> 10:11.694
- Why did you get rid
of Mrs. Findley?

10:11.777 --> 10:15.323
- She wasn't up to it,
not for what I have in mind.

10:15.406 --> 10:16.699
- Hmm.

10:16.782 --> 10:18.826
Did you know
they shot Jesse James?

10:18.909 --> 10:20.911
- He had his troubles.
I have mine.

10:22.913 --> 10:24.040
What--
[chuckles]

10:24.123 --> 10:26.042
- Mm.

10:26.125 --> 10:29.086
So how was your afternoon?

10:29.170 --> 10:30.755
- I've left cards
with Mrs. Stevens,

10:30.838 --> 10:33.090
Mrs. Rutherfurd, Mrs. Jones,
Mrs. Vanderbilt,

10:33.174 --> 10:35.885
Mrs. Schermerhorn,
and Mrs. Astor, of course.

10:35.968 --> 10:39.347
- Of course.
- So now they know we're here.

10:39.430 --> 10:42.224
- We have been in New York City
for three years, Bertha,

10:42.308 --> 10:43.893
watching this house
rise from the sidewalk.

10:43.976 --> 10:45.603
- But we've been stuck
down on 30th Street

10:45.686 --> 10:46.854
with yesterday's men.

10:46.937 --> 10:47.897
- You chose the house.

10:47.980 --> 10:49.023
- I didn't know
how things worked then.

10:49.106 --> 10:50.066
Now I do.

10:50.149 --> 10:51.734
The point is, we're settled
where we should be,

10:51.817 --> 10:54.236
and that's what
I wanted to show them.

10:54.320 --> 10:57.031
- They don't care.
They don't know we exist.

10:57.114 --> 10:58.157
- Well, they will now,

10:58.240 --> 10:59.867
and there's no need
to sound superior.

10:59.950 --> 11:02.328
We cannot succeed in this town
without Mrs. Astor's approval.

11:02.411 --> 11:03.537
I know that much.

11:03.621 --> 11:05.289
- So we are to bow down
before a woman

11:05.373 --> 11:06.749
who has less money than me,

11:06.832 --> 11:09.668
and less of
absolutely everything than you.

11:11.003 --> 11:12.755
- I'm only doing it for you,

11:12.838 --> 11:14.423
and Larry and Gladys,
of course.

11:14.507 --> 11:15.758
- Of course.

11:15.841 --> 11:16.926
- I want people to see

11:17.009 --> 11:18.302
they come
from a good background.

11:18.386 --> 11:20.763
They'd be lucky to welcome them
into their homes.

11:20.846 --> 11:22.723
- Would they be lucky
to welcome me into their homes,

11:22.807 --> 11:23.933
or you?

11:24.016 --> 11:26.268
- You can laugh,
but we'll get there.

11:26.352 --> 11:27.978
I just have
to manage it carefully.

11:28.062 --> 11:29.814
- The Russell family
has managed

11:29.897 --> 11:31.565
pretty well so far,
if you ask me.

11:31.649 --> 11:33.734
- Because they didn't know
any better.

11:33.818 --> 11:35.152
Mrs. Van Rhijn
and her sad sister

11:35.236 --> 11:36.987
were spying on me
when I came back.

11:37.071 --> 11:39.240
- I don't know
why you bother with them.

11:39.323 --> 11:40.741
- I don't bother with them.

11:42.993 --> 11:45.955
Careful, that table belonged
to King Ludwig of Bavaria.

11:46.038 --> 11:48.249
- He had it once.
I've got it now.

11:48.332 --> 11:49.875
- I'm going up to change.

11:49.959 --> 11:51.502
I want to get
out of this corset.

11:51.585 --> 11:55.631
♪ ♪

11:55.714 --> 11:57.842
[indistinct chatter]

11:57.925 --> 11:59.844
Church, could you tell Turner
I've gone to my room?

11:59.927 --> 12:01.512
- She is
already upstairs, madam.

12:01.595 --> 12:03.472
- Is Miss Gladys
back from her walk?

12:03.556 --> 12:05.141
- She's with Miss Grant
in the school room.

12:05.224 --> 12:07.518
- And is everything ready
for Mr. Larry's return?

12:07.601 --> 12:08.477
- I believe so, madam,

12:08.561 --> 12:09.979
but I will check
with Mrs. Bruce.

12:10.062 --> 12:12.273
- Thank you, Church.

12:12.356 --> 12:13.732
- Yes, once more...

12:13.816 --> 12:16.777
[indistinct chatter]

12:16.861 --> 12:18.737
- She's gone up to change.

12:18.821 --> 12:22.032
- And he won't be long.
I should go.

12:22.116 --> 12:23.951
- Tell him I'm making a list

12:24.034 --> 12:25.828
of what is not right
about this kitchen.

12:25.911 --> 12:27.288
- The master won't bother
with that.

12:27.371 --> 12:30.291
I'll tell the mistress
what you want, if you mean it.

12:30.374 --> 12:32.293
- I think
it's going to work well.

12:32.376 --> 12:33.711
It's far bigger
than the last place.

12:33.794 --> 12:36.839
You didn't mind that.
- It was only rented.

12:36.922 --> 12:39.175
Abandoned by its owner
because 30th Street

12:39.258 --> 12:40.509
is out of fashion.

12:40.593 --> 12:43.596
Why complain about a house
when it's rented?

12:43.679 --> 12:45.848
- I'd say this is
three times the size.

12:45.931 --> 12:47.641
If you ask me, we're well-off.

12:47.725 --> 12:50.478
- Shouldn't you be on your way
upstairs, Mr. Watson?

12:50.561 --> 12:57.485
♪ ♪

13:00.738 --> 13:02.198
- Oh, Mrs. Bauer,

13:02.281 --> 13:04.825
I hope she won't make
extra work for you.

13:04.909 --> 13:07.828
Miss Marian, I mean.
You must say if it's too much.

13:07.912 --> 13:09.663
- Oh, I don't mind.

13:09.747 --> 13:12.500
I think she may
brighten the place up a bit.

13:12.583 --> 13:16.337
- Yes, that's rather what
Mrs. Van Rhijn is afraid of.

13:17.796 --> 13:19.715
[horses neighing]

13:19.798 --> 13:22.718
[people shouting indistinctly]

13:22.801 --> 13:29.767
♪ ♪

13:37.775 --> 13:39.735
- Morning, sir.

13:52.122 --> 13:55.251
- That'll be all.
Thank you, Miss Ainsley.

13:56.919 --> 13:58.837
I'd say we're all set
for a clear run

13:58.921 --> 14:00.297
from New York to Chicago.

14:00.381 --> 14:03.092
- Mr. Thorburn is still
making trouble on his stretch.

14:03.175 --> 14:05.135
- Mm, from Cleveland to Toledo?
- Mm.

14:05.219 --> 14:06.845
- I don't care much.

14:06.929 --> 14:09.265
- What will you do
if he won't play ball?

14:09.348 --> 14:12.351
- Build another line,
right alongside his.

14:12.434 --> 14:13.769
It'll show the world
we mean business.

14:13.852 --> 14:16.438
- And ruin Thorburn
in the process.

14:16.522 --> 14:18.899
- You can't make an omelet
without breaking eggs.

14:18.983 --> 14:20.734
- Then the next step
is for the city aldermen

14:20.818 --> 14:22.861
to grant permission
for the new station.

14:22.945 --> 14:24.446
- Grant permission?

14:24.530 --> 14:26.407
You make them sound
very important.

14:26.490 --> 14:28.617
- Not half as important
as they think they are,

14:28.701 --> 14:31.245
but the fact remains,
we need them to pass the law.

14:31.328 --> 14:33.247
- Have we got a list
of their names?

14:33.330 --> 14:35.082
- Right here.

14:36.709 --> 14:38.460
Shall I round up
our detectives,

14:38.544 --> 14:40.296
see if they can dig up
anything useful?

14:40.379 --> 14:41.463
- Not yet.

14:41.547 --> 14:44.258
We'll start by appealing
to their greed.

14:44.341 --> 14:46.802
But do nothing now.
I'll tell you when to begin.

14:46.885 --> 14:49.805
[soft dramatic music]

14:49.888 --> 14:55.185
♪ ♪

15:02.192 --> 15:04.653
- You're kind to take me
at such an early hour.

15:04.737 --> 15:05.904
- Not at all.

15:05.988 --> 15:08.282
- There is only a bed
and a chair left,

15:08.365 --> 15:10.576
so perhaps you could give those
to a charity.

15:12.536 --> 15:15.956
- Have you slept at all?
You look worn out.

15:16.040 --> 15:19.293
- Just what every woman
wants to hear.

15:19.376 --> 15:20.836
- [sighs]

15:20.919 --> 15:22.212
[clicks tongue]

15:22.296 --> 15:25.215
[soft orchestral music]

15:25.299 --> 15:27.760
♪ ♪

15:27.843 --> 15:29.637
This is the receipt
for your trunk.

15:29.720 --> 15:31.972
It should be delivered
this evening.

15:32.056 --> 15:34.767
Can you manage until then?
- I can.

15:34.850 --> 15:37.019
You're not to wait.
- Oh, I don't mind.

15:37.102 --> 15:38.729
- No, I insist.

15:38.812 --> 15:40.606
You have to get on,
and the train won't be long.

15:42.066 --> 15:44.443
- Well, I guess this is it.

15:44.526 --> 15:46.487
I'm sorry you're going,
Miss Brook.

15:46.570 --> 15:48.989
May I say that without offense?

15:49.073 --> 15:51.033
- But you're glad
I will be taken care of.

15:51.116 --> 15:53.494
I understand.

15:53.577 --> 15:55.329
You have my address
in New York.

15:55.412 --> 15:58.832
- I do.
May I write to you?

15:58.916 --> 16:01.877
- I don't think so, Mr. Raikes.

16:01.960 --> 16:04.046
- I only meant if there was
any further business,

16:04.129 --> 16:05.506
business to be dealt with.
- Oh, I'm--

16:07.174 --> 16:08.717
I see.

16:08.801 --> 16:10.678
Well, in that case,
I suppose you'll need to.

16:13.639 --> 16:17.059
- I'll say goodbye, Miss Brook,
and good luck on your travels.

16:17.142 --> 16:18.435
- And good luck to you.

16:18.519 --> 16:21.480
[train whistle blowing]

16:25.818 --> 16:26.860
- [clicks tongue]

16:26.944 --> 16:28.696
[horse nickers]

16:37.454 --> 16:39.081
- What do you mean,
you don't know where it is?

16:39.164 --> 16:40.874
- I don't know.
How is that hard?

16:40.958 --> 16:43.544
- You're a damn liar.
- What'd you call me?

16:43.627 --> 16:45.421
[both grunting]

16:45.504 --> 16:47.131
- Break it up!

16:47.214 --> 16:48.257
- Ah!
- Oh!

16:48.340 --> 16:49.508
- Get back here, you bastard!

16:50.843 --> 16:51.760
[fabric rips]

16:51.844 --> 16:54.346
- Oh. Ah.
I'm so sorry about that.

16:54.430 --> 16:57.474
- Oh, it's all right.
I can fix it.

16:57.558 --> 16:59.268
They've gone.

16:59.351 --> 17:00.811
- That was
the most frightful thing.

17:00.894 --> 17:03.063
[train whistle blows]

17:03.147 --> 17:04.231
- Train for Lansdale.

17:04.314 --> 17:07.359
[brakes squeak]

17:07.443 --> 17:08.819
- My purse.

17:11.989 --> 17:15.367
- Have your tickets ready.
- Here you are, sir.

17:20.664 --> 17:23.959
- Excuse me, sir,
my ticket was in my purse.

17:24.042 --> 17:25.461
There were two men fighting,
and somehow,

17:25.544 --> 17:27.671
it must have been taken
during the commotion.

17:27.755 --> 17:29.465
- Sorry, miss.

17:29.548 --> 17:31.675
- No, please, sir,
I have to get to New York.

17:31.759 --> 17:32.801
- Not without a ticket.

17:32.885 --> 17:35.804
[dramatic orchestral music]

17:35.888 --> 17:42.853
♪ ♪

17:46.356 --> 17:48.233
- You haven't seen a purse,
by any chance?

17:48.317 --> 17:50.152
- I'm afraid not.

17:50.235 --> 17:52.529
- It had my train
and ferry tickets and my money,

17:52.613 --> 17:54.656
and I don't know
what I'm going to do.

17:54.740 --> 17:57.284
- Are you from around here?
- Yes.

17:57.367 --> 17:59.161
- Can't you go home to get
money for the next train?

17:59.244 --> 18:00.871
- There is no home
to go back to.

18:02.289 --> 18:04.249
And anyway,
my trunk's on this one.

18:05.667 --> 18:07.836
- I'm so sorry.

18:10.255 --> 18:11.215
- This isn't your concern.

18:11.298 --> 18:13.467
Please, don't let me
hold you up.

18:13.550 --> 18:15.135
- We have to board last.

18:16.929 --> 18:18.347
- Oh, I see.

18:27.564 --> 18:30.484
[sobbing]

18:30.567 --> 18:37.533
♪ ♪

18:42.746 --> 18:45.749
[coughing]

18:49.169 --> 18:51.839
- I'm sorry
it's not first class.

18:51.922 --> 18:53.715
- Nonsense.
You've been very kind,

18:53.799 --> 18:55.342
especially when
I tore your skirt.

18:56.969 --> 18:58.762
I promise, my aunts are
good for the money.

18:58.846 --> 19:00.180
- I imagine they are

19:00.264 --> 19:02.891
if they live
on East 61st Street.

19:02.975 --> 19:04.852
- So you know New York?

19:04.935 --> 19:06.436
- My parents live in Brooklyn.
- Oh.

19:06.520 --> 19:07.938
- I grew up there.

19:09.189 --> 19:10.649
- This is my first trip.

19:10.732 --> 19:12.943
- Mm.

19:13.026 --> 19:14.653
- You must give me
your parents' address

19:14.736 --> 19:16.196
to send the money.

19:16.280 --> 19:17.906
- I don't know
if I'll be staying with them.

19:17.990 --> 19:20.325
I have some business
that needs looking into,

19:20.409 --> 19:21.660
but I'm not sure
where I'll be based.

19:21.743 --> 19:23.537
- Then how shall I repay you?

19:23.620 --> 19:25.706
- I'll come to your
aunts' house in a day or two,

19:25.789 --> 19:27.541
if you could leave an envelope
to be collected.

19:27.624 --> 19:29.251
- Of course.

19:31.169 --> 19:34.089
[soaring music]

19:34.173 --> 19:41.138
♪ ♪

19:42.514 --> 19:44.141
- Well?

19:44.224 --> 19:45.809
- I guess it's big enough.

19:45.893 --> 19:47.060
- If you're going
to do a thing,

19:47.144 --> 19:48.937
you might as well
do it properly.

19:49.021 --> 19:50.898
What do you think
of the paneling in your room?

19:50.981 --> 19:52.065
- Why?

19:52.149 --> 19:54.359
- Mr. White found it
in the Château de Chavaniac,

19:54.443 --> 19:55.652
the home of Lafayette.

19:55.736 --> 19:58.405
- It's very fine,
but I should get going.

19:58.488 --> 20:00.574
I'm catching the 11:00 train
to Rhode Island.

20:00.657 --> 20:01.783
- But you've only
just got home.

20:01.867 --> 20:03.702
- [chuckles]
Is that what this is?

20:03.785 --> 20:05.120
- Well, take a later train
at least.

20:05.203 --> 20:06.496
We haven't seen you
all semester.

20:06.580 --> 20:07.456
- But it'll be fun.

20:07.539 --> 20:09.082
It's the one
Mrs. Fish told us to catch,

20:09.166 --> 20:10.918
and most of the party
are traveling on it.

20:11.001 --> 20:12.252
- Who is in the party?
Do you know?

20:12.336 --> 20:13.295
- The usual crowd.

20:13.378 --> 20:15.672
Ogden Goelet and his wife,
the Joneses,

20:15.756 --> 20:17.841
the Wilsons, Carrie Astor--

20:17.925 --> 20:19.009
- Carrie Astor?

20:19.092 --> 20:20.510
- I think so.
- DO you know her?

20:20.594 --> 20:22.512
You never said.
- I don't, not really.

20:22.596 --> 20:24.181
Not much.
- Then get to know her.

20:24.264 --> 20:25.641
And catch that train.
- Mother.

20:25.724 --> 20:27.809
- I know what I'm doing.

20:27.893 --> 20:30.228
- We've finished the gilding
in the ballroom, Mrs. Russell.

20:30.312 --> 20:31.939
- No, you think you have
finished the gilding,

20:32.022 --> 20:34.066
Mr. Kowalski, but nothing
is finished till I decide.

20:34.149 --> 20:35.776
- I'm going, Mother.
Where is Gladys?

20:35.859 --> 20:37.402
- Why?
- I want to say goodbye to her.

20:37.486 --> 20:38.445
- I'll say it for you.

20:38.528 --> 20:39.863
She's gone to the park
with Miss Grant.

20:39.947 --> 20:41.365
- She's not a child anymore,

20:41.448 --> 20:42.616
and you shouldn't treat her
as one.

20:42.699 --> 20:45.285
- She's a child until I say.
Where are your bags?

20:45.369 --> 20:46.954
- My trunk
will be delivered tomorrow,

20:47.037 --> 20:48.538
and what I need
for Newport's in the carriage.

20:48.622 --> 20:51.708
- Then hurry, and give
my regards to Mrs. Fish.

20:51.792 --> 20:53.293
- Don't be silly.
You don't know her.

20:53.377 --> 20:55.003
- Not yet, but I will.

20:55.087 --> 20:56.463
Now, come along, Mr. Kowalski,

20:56.546 --> 20:58.465
show me
what you think you've done.

20:58.548 --> 21:01.468
[plucky music]

21:01.551 --> 21:04.471
[indistinct chatter]

21:04.554 --> 21:11.520
♪ ♪

21:14.272 --> 21:15.565
- Here it comes now.

21:15.649 --> 21:18.151
- I don't like
the look of that sky.

21:18.235 --> 21:21.196
[ship horn blares]

21:24.408 --> 21:26.410
So this is to be my home.

21:28.120 --> 21:31.999
Funny, I never imagined I'd be
wistful for Pennsylvania.

21:32.082 --> 21:34.668
- Then why did you leave?

21:34.751 --> 21:36.628
- There is nothing there
for me anymore,

21:36.712 --> 21:38.714
not since my father died.

21:38.797 --> 21:40.507
- Oh, I'm so sorry.

21:42.759 --> 21:44.845
- Will you go to Brooklyn now?

21:44.928 --> 21:47.097
- I suppose so.

21:47.180 --> 21:48.765
It's too late for me
to make another plan,

21:48.849 --> 21:52.352
and I can catch the last ferry,
even if I don't much want to.

21:53.770 --> 21:55.856
- Well, I hope
it all works out for you,

21:55.939 --> 21:58.275
and once again,
thank you for what you did.

21:58.358 --> 22:01.236
Please ask for me
when you come for the money.

22:01.319 --> 22:03.780
- Of course, and good luck
with your aunts.

22:05.323 --> 22:06.825
- Desbrosses Street ferry
coming in.

22:06.908 --> 22:07.826
- That's us.

22:07.909 --> 22:10.203
- Desbrosses Street ferry
coming in.

22:10.287 --> 22:11.997
[ship horn blaring]
- Tickets. Tickets.

22:12.080 --> 22:13.081
Tickets please!

22:13.165 --> 22:15.333
- Desbrosses Street ferry
coming in!

22:15.417 --> 22:22.424
♪ ♪

22:24.676 --> 22:26.928
[thunderclap]

22:27.012 --> 22:28.472
- How are things at the office?

22:28.555 --> 22:30.599
- Don't start him on that,
I beg you.

22:30.682 --> 22:33.435
- I suppose father's business
is what we all depend on.

22:33.518 --> 22:34.811
[thunder rumbles]

22:34.895 --> 22:37.105
- I hope the weather
is better in Newport.

22:37.189 --> 22:38.565
When does Larry come back?

22:38.648 --> 22:40.442
- Not before the day
after tomorrow.

22:40.525 --> 22:42.819
- I suppose he has
some oats to sow

22:42.903 --> 22:44.696
now that college is over.

22:44.780 --> 22:47.991
- When will he start with you?
- Straight away, I imagine.

22:48.075 --> 22:50.911
Nothing to be gained
from delay.

22:50.994 --> 22:53.872
Why not invite your sister
to stay for a while?

22:53.955 --> 22:56.416
- I don't think so.

22:56.500 --> 22:59.169
- What about your old friends?
You never see them now.

22:59.252 --> 23:01.671
- I don't want my old friends.
I want new friends.

23:05.717 --> 23:08.804
[soft orchestral music]

23:08.887 --> 23:15.852
♪ ♪

23:17.854 --> 23:18.814
[thunder rumbles]

23:18.897 --> 23:20.148
[horse neighing]

23:20.232 --> 23:21.817
- Whoa, hey!
- That's enough of that.

23:25.237 --> 23:26.613
- Wait.

23:27.697 --> 23:29.324
Give me a moment.

23:33.537 --> 23:34.496
Come with me.

23:34.579 --> 23:36.456
Let us
at least give you a ride.

23:36.540 --> 23:37.916
- Thank you.

23:41.920 --> 23:45.006
- Can we take her
to the Brooklyn ferry?

23:45.090 --> 23:47.217
- No ferrys are running,
not in this weather.

23:47.300 --> 23:49.302
- I'll be fine.

23:49.386 --> 23:50.887
- I'm not leaving without you.

23:50.971 --> 23:52.514
[thunder rumbles]

23:52.597 --> 23:53.974
- Very well.

23:54.057 --> 24:00.981
♪ ♪

24:05.402 --> 24:06.820
[bell rings]

24:06.903 --> 24:09.698
- Oh, that's her now.
- It is.

24:09.781 --> 24:12.033
Come on, John.
Look lively.

24:12.117 --> 24:13.827
- I wonder what she'll be like.

24:13.910 --> 24:16.163
- Well, we'll know soon enough.

24:16.246 --> 24:18.957
[plucky orchestral music]

24:19.040 --> 24:24.379
♪ ♪

24:24.462 --> 24:26.965
- Welcome to East 61st Street,
Miss Marian.

24:27.048 --> 24:29.551
My name is Bannister,
Mrs. Van Rhijn's butler.

24:31.428 --> 24:33.471
And this is?

24:35.307 --> 24:38.226
- Miss Scott.
Miss Peggy Scott.

24:38.310 --> 24:40.145
- Miss Scott traveled with me,

24:40.228 --> 24:42.022
but they've canceled
the ferries to Brooklyn.

24:42.105 --> 24:43.607
I'm rather hoping
Mrs. Van Rhijn

24:43.690 --> 24:46.026
will allow her to rest here
until the storm has passed.

24:46.109 --> 24:47.152
- I see.

24:47.235 --> 24:49.863
Mrs. van Rhijn's in
the drawing room with Miss Ada.

24:49.946 --> 24:51.323
- Then I'll ask them.

24:51.406 --> 24:53.533
If Miss Scott
could wait downstairs?

24:53.617 --> 24:54.993
- Of course.

24:55.076 --> 25:02.042
♪ ♪

25:03.501 --> 25:06.296
- An unknown colored woman
lent you money

25:06.379 --> 25:07.923
to travel to New York?

25:08.006 --> 25:09.716
That seems very unlikely.

25:09.799 --> 25:11.551
- Unlikely or not, it's true.

25:11.635 --> 25:12.928
- And she's here, now?

25:13.011 --> 25:14.262
- Well, her parents
live in Brooklyn,

25:14.346 --> 25:16.348
but the cab driver said
the ferries aren't running.

25:16.431 --> 25:18.433
- Well, then of course
she must stay.

25:18.516 --> 25:20.936
Mustn't she, Agnes?

25:21.019 --> 25:22.938
- Bring her in first.

25:23.021 --> 25:25.690
I have to meet anyone
who's going to be in my house.

25:25.774 --> 25:26.942
- Of course, ma'am.

25:28.610 --> 25:31.696
- Marian, you must be hungry.
- Not really.

25:31.780 --> 25:34.282
- We'll have Mrs. Bauer
send something up to her room.

25:40.080 --> 25:42.082
It seems we owe you
a considerable debt,

25:42.165 --> 25:43.667
Miss Scott.

25:43.750 --> 25:45.961
I gather you would like
to stay here?

25:46.044 --> 25:47.796
- I don't want
to be a nuisance.

25:47.879 --> 25:49.506
- I forced Miss Scott
into the cab

25:49.589 --> 25:50.840
to get her out of the storm.

25:50.924 --> 25:52.509
- The wind gusts alone
could blow you

25:52.592 --> 25:53.969
all the way to Fifth Avenue.

25:54.052 --> 25:55.845
- So she can stay, Aunt Agnes?

25:57.889 --> 26:00.976
- We can't have Miss Scott
blown into oblivion.

26:01.059 --> 26:02.978
Yes, you may stay,
and in the morning,

26:03.061 --> 26:05.647
Bannister can fetch the money
from the bank to repay you.

26:05.730 --> 26:06.773
- Thank you.

26:06.856 --> 26:10.110
I have never found myself
in such an odd predicament.

26:10.193 --> 26:11.778
I appreciate your kindness.

26:11.861 --> 26:13.488
- You may stay
on one condition:

26:13.571 --> 26:15.282
that you give me
your parents' address

26:15.365 --> 26:17.284
in case anything happens.

26:17.367 --> 26:18.660
- Nothing will happen to me.

26:18.743 --> 26:20.662
- I won't be in a position
of having no one to contact

26:20.745 --> 26:22.289
if it does.

26:22.372 --> 26:24.207
- Very well.

26:28.253 --> 26:31.298
- I hope the ferry crossing
wasn't too rough, dear.

26:31.381 --> 26:32.966
- No, not at all.

26:39.639 --> 26:41.224
- Who taught you
to write like this?

26:41.308 --> 26:43.059
- The Institute
for Colored Youth

26:43.143 --> 26:45.020
in Philadelphia.

26:45.103 --> 26:46.646
- But I know it well.

26:46.730 --> 26:48.315
My father was a patron

26:48.398 --> 26:49.983
when it first opened
in the '30s.

26:50.066 --> 26:52.819
I grew up in Pennsylvania,
outside Doylestown.

26:52.902 --> 26:54.237
- We used to attend

26:54.321 --> 26:55.989
the wonderful
Christmas pageants

26:56.072 --> 26:57.198
at the school.

26:57.282 --> 26:59.534
Were you a part of that?
- Every year.

26:59.617 --> 27:00.535
- Oh!
[laughs]

27:00.618 --> 27:01.911
- Let's get you settled,
Miss Scott,

27:01.995 --> 27:03.955
before my sister begs you
to sing a carol.

27:04.039 --> 27:05.498
- [laughs]

27:05.582 --> 27:06.458
- Go down to the kitchens

27:06.541 --> 27:08.168
and ask Mrs. Bauer
to find you a room.

27:08.251 --> 27:09.210
- Thank you.

27:10.462 --> 27:12.464
- [laughs]

27:14.841 --> 27:19.054
- Now, Marian,
have you made any plans yet?

27:19.137 --> 27:22.182
- She's only
just arrived, Agnes.

27:22.265 --> 27:24.017
- I haven't made any plans, no.

27:24.100 --> 27:25.894
- I suppose
you only recently learned

27:25.977 --> 27:27.937
that your father
had let you down.

27:28.021 --> 27:30.315
- Please don't speak ill
of Daddy.

27:30.398 --> 27:31.733
- I will say what I like
in my own house.

27:31.816 --> 27:33.443
- Not to me.

27:35.945 --> 27:37.238
I thought I might find a job.

27:37.322 --> 27:38.782
- [gasps]

27:38.865 --> 27:40.533
- Would that be
out of the question?

27:40.617 --> 27:42.869
- Only if you wish
to live with me.

27:42.952 --> 27:44.204
- Well, I don't want
to be idle.

27:44.287 --> 27:46.706
Perhaps there's a charity
that could use my services.

27:46.790 --> 27:49.417
- How generous,
and how suitable.

27:49.501 --> 27:51.711
- That depends
on the charity she chooses,

27:51.795 --> 27:54.381
but first we must attend
to your clothes, my dear.

27:54.464 --> 27:56.925
You will go tomorrow with Ada
to my dressmaker,

27:57.008 --> 27:58.426
and no black.

27:58.510 --> 27:59.719
- But I'm in mourning.

27:59.803 --> 28:01.805
- People here won't know
when Henry died.

28:01.888 --> 28:03.681
You're making your debut
in society.

28:03.765 --> 28:05.058
You are young and pretty

28:05.141 --> 28:07.268
and need to be shown
to advantage.

28:07.352 --> 28:09.354
I don't want you hanging about
on the edge of things

28:09.437 --> 28:10.438
like a lonely crow.

28:10.522 --> 28:11.731
Ada, remember,

28:11.815 --> 28:13.525
I want cheerful colors,
whatever she says.

28:13.608 --> 28:14.526
- But--

28:14.609 --> 28:16.361
- We must look out
for some people

28:16.444 --> 28:18.363
with sons and daughters
your age.

28:18.446 --> 28:20.907
- That's true.
I don't know anyone.

28:20.990 --> 28:22.575
- Now, you need to know
we only receive

28:22.659 --> 28:25.537
the old people in this house,

28:25.620 --> 28:27.038
not the new.

28:27.122 --> 28:29.749
Never the new.
- What's the difference?

28:29.833 --> 28:32.293
- The old have been in charge
since before the revolution.

28:32.377 --> 28:35.630
They ruled justly
until the new people invaded.

28:35.713 --> 28:38.174
- It's not quite as simple
as that.

28:38.258 --> 28:40.301
- Yes, it is.
- Well, I'm new.

28:40.385 --> 28:41.344
I've only just arrived.

28:41.428 --> 28:43.179
- Marian,
never mind that the Brooks

28:43.263 --> 28:46.641
have been in Pennsylvania
for a century and a half.

28:46.724 --> 28:49.769
My mother, your grandmother,
was a Livingston

28:49.853 --> 28:51.187
of Livingston Manor,

28:51.271 --> 28:55.066
and they came to this city
in 1674.

28:55.150 --> 28:56.818
You belong to old New York,
my dear,

28:56.901 --> 28:59.320
and don't let anyone
tell you different.

28:59.404 --> 29:01.322
You are my niece,

29:01.406 --> 29:03.992
and you belong to old New York.

29:04.075 --> 29:11.040
♪ ♪

29:17.130 --> 29:20.008
- Wil you fetch Miss Scott
some supper, Bridget?

29:20.091 --> 29:21.217
- I don't want
to be any trouble.

29:21.301 --> 29:23.011
- No, no, please, sit down.

29:27.265 --> 29:29.225
I hope they've made a room
ready for you.

29:29.309 --> 29:30.518
- Oh, we had one prepared

29:30.602 --> 29:32.729
in case Miss Marian
brought a maid.

29:32.812 --> 29:33.688
- Mm-hmm.

29:33.771 --> 29:35.064
Mrs. Bauer is on the top floor

29:35.148 --> 29:37.484
with you and Miss Armstrong
and Bridget.

29:37.567 --> 29:39.986
John and I sleep down here.

29:40.069 --> 29:42.197
- She's on the same floor
as us?

29:42.280 --> 29:43.656
- Is there some difficulty?

29:45.283 --> 29:46.910
Ah, there you are, then.

29:48.203 --> 29:51.456
- Do you drink coffee?

29:51.539 --> 29:52.832
- Yes, I drink coffee.

29:52.916 --> 29:54.918
Thank you.

29:55.001 --> 29:56.377
- [sighs]

29:56.461 --> 29:58.505
- I just wanted to be sure.

30:04.385 --> 30:06.054
- But are we to share
the same bathroom,

30:06.137 --> 30:07.889
the same water closet?

30:07.972 --> 30:09.891
- She can hardly use a bucket
under the stairs.

30:09.974 --> 30:11.684
- Is that right, Mr. Bannister?

30:11.768 --> 30:14.020
- It's not for us
to have an opinion.

30:14.103 --> 30:15.813
- I don't want trouble
in the house,

30:15.897 --> 30:17.065
and while she may not
want to cause it,

30:17.148 --> 30:18.525
she may be the cause of it.

30:18.608 --> 30:21.611
- I repeat, it is not for us
to have an opinion,

30:21.694 --> 30:22.862
certainly not that one.

30:22.946 --> 30:25.615
- But how long is she here for,
and why is she here at all?

30:25.698 --> 30:27.367
- Because she performed
a great service

30:27.450 --> 30:28.409
for Miss Marian.

30:28.493 --> 30:30.245
- I'm going to bed.
- Good night.

30:30.328 --> 30:32.205
- I think that Miss Scott
seems nice.

30:32.288 --> 30:34.374
- Which is all you know.
- Yes, it is.

30:34.457 --> 30:36.668
And I'm sticking to it
until she proves me wrong.

30:36.751 --> 30:38.586
- That's all very well
for you to say,

30:38.670 --> 30:40.630
but they're coming up here now
to take our jobs.

30:40.713 --> 30:42.632
- She's not taking
anyone's job.

30:42.715 --> 30:44.425
- See?
She'll disrupt things.

30:44.509 --> 30:46.427
I told Mrs. Bauer,
but she wouldn't listen.

30:46.511 --> 30:48.388
- Maybe we need
a bit of disruption.

30:50.014 --> 30:51.641
- Ugh.

30:55.019 --> 30:55.979
- Oh.

30:58.773 --> 31:00.358
Excuse me.

31:04.654 --> 31:05.780
[door slams]

31:05.863 --> 31:07.282
[lock clicks]

31:19.127 --> 31:21.296
- Miss Scott, I think
this is what we owe you.

31:21.379 --> 31:22.297
- Thank you.

31:22.380 --> 31:24.048
- While he was out,
Bannister checked,

31:24.132 --> 31:26.092
and the Brooklyn ferry
is still not running.

31:26.175 --> 31:28.344
The docks were damaged
in the storm.

31:28.428 --> 31:30.763
You may have to stay here
another night.

31:30.847 --> 31:32.974
Will your family be concerned?

31:33.057 --> 31:35.476
- They weren't expecting me,
so no.

31:35.560 --> 31:37.312
- Really?

31:37.395 --> 31:38.896
Oh, thank you.

31:38.980 --> 31:40.607
I'm overwhelmed with papers.

31:40.690 --> 31:43.109
I've never been this behind
on my correspondence.

31:43.192 --> 31:44.736
- Mrs. Van Rhijn,
please tell me

31:44.819 --> 31:47.447
if there's anything
I can do to help.

31:47.530 --> 31:49.115
- Well, you do have
the penmanship for it.

31:49.198 --> 31:52.619
- I can take dictation.
I know Pitman shorthand.

31:52.702 --> 31:54.704
It's the least I can do
to repay you.

31:56.539 --> 31:59.626
- I will dictate some letters,
if you insist,

31:59.709 --> 32:02.211
but they will only be
very dull ones, I'm afraid.

32:02.295 --> 32:04.088
[both laugh]

32:08.968 --> 32:10.219
- Gladys, that's bad
for your eyes.

32:10.303 --> 32:11.679
Sit nearer the window.

32:11.763 --> 32:13.514
[door clicks]

32:13.598 --> 32:15.016
- Just delivered by hand,
ma'am.

32:15.099 --> 32:16.059
- Thank you, Church.

32:21.230 --> 32:22.815
[door clicks]

32:22.899 --> 32:24.484
A Mrs. Morris and a Mrs. Fane

32:24.567 --> 32:26.986
want me to support a charity
in aid of orphaned girls.

32:27.070 --> 32:29.614
- Is that Mrs. Patrick Morris
and Mrs. Charles Fane?

32:29.697 --> 32:31.532
- Uh, yes it is.
Why?

32:31.616 --> 32:34.160
- Their husbands
are city aldermen.

32:34.243 --> 32:35.328
I may have some business
with them.

32:35.411 --> 32:36.621
What do the wives want of you?

32:36.704 --> 32:38.039
- Well, to start with,
there's a meeting

32:38.122 --> 32:40.333
for friends of the cause to be
held at the Fifth Avenue Hotel.

32:40.416 --> 32:42.752
- Really?
Not in one of their own houses?

32:42.835 --> 32:44.420
- I dare say
a hotel was more convenient.

32:44.504 --> 32:46.673
- I hear
the Fifth Avenue's slipping.

32:46.756 --> 32:48.549
No one wants to be
down on 23rd Street anymore.

32:48.633 --> 32:50.760
- I won't let you spoil it
for me.

32:50.843 --> 32:52.261
- I don't want to spoil it.

32:52.345 --> 32:54.389
- It's beginning.
I knew it would.

32:54.472 --> 32:56.057
Persistence is the key
to everything.

32:56.140 --> 32:57.392
Patience and persistence.

32:57.475 --> 32:59.060
- Useful qualities, I agree.

32:59.143 --> 33:01.187
- Could I come, Mother, please?

33:01.270 --> 33:03.022
- Take her.
Why not?

33:04.273 --> 33:06.526
- I'll think about it.
- When is it?

33:06.609 --> 33:08.069
- On the 1st.

33:08.152 --> 33:09.654
- I'm seeing John Thorburn
that day.

33:09.737 --> 33:10.863
- Who's he?

33:10.947 --> 33:11.864
- A man who owns a railroad

33:11.948 --> 33:13.658
and thinks he can
get the better of me.

33:13.741 --> 33:14.867
- He'll find out.

33:17.120 --> 33:19.372
Nicely done, Miss Scott.
Thank you.

33:19.455 --> 33:20.373
- Not at all.

33:20.456 --> 33:22.208
- Look who I found in my room.

33:22.291 --> 33:24.085
- Must we have
that horrid thing in here?

33:24.168 --> 33:26.295
- I think we must.
Don't you, Aunt Ada?

33:26.379 --> 33:29.757
- Absolutely.

33:29.841 --> 33:32.385
Have you had a nice walk, dear?
- I have.

33:32.468 --> 33:34.887
Your suitcase is mended.
I brought it back myself.

33:34.971 --> 33:35.930
- Oh.
- I've put it in your room.

33:36.013 --> 33:38.474
- You carried a suitcase
through the streets?

33:38.558 --> 33:40.643
- Oh, have I broken
another rule?

33:40.727 --> 33:41.978
- You were to check
it was ready

33:42.061 --> 33:43.896
and then send the footman
to collect it.

33:43.980 --> 33:45.732
And never go out unaccompanied.

33:45.815 --> 33:47.817
Please don't do
such a thing again.

33:47.900 --> 33:49.652
- I should leave you.

33:49.736 --> 33:52.280
- Miss Scott,
I've just had another thought.

33:52.363 --> 33:56.200
Clearly, I'm in need of help
with my correspondence.

33:56.284 --> 33:57.577
I don't know
what your plans are,

33:57.660 --> 33:58.703
but if you're interested,

33:58.786 --> 34:01.497
I would like to hire you
as my secretary.

34:01.581 --> 34:03.124
- That does interest me.

34:03.207 --> 34:05.084
- I would need a reference,
of course.

34:05.168 --> 34:06.461
- I can get you one
from the principal

34:06.544 --> 34:08.129
at the institute.

34:08.212 --> 34:11.758
But working on 61st
and staying in Brooklyn

34:11.841 --> 34:12.842
presents a challenge,

34:12.925 --> 34:14.469
even once the ferries
are running.

34:15.845 --> 34:18.264
- It seems to me, Miss Scott,
that you are not eager

34:18.347 --> 34:20.641
to return home.

34:20.725 --> 34:21.809
Very well.

34:21.893 --> 34:23.811
You may stay here
for the time being,

34:23.895 --> 34:26.063
but you must arrange
to see your parents

34:26.147 --> 34:27.774
and tell them where you are.

34:27.857 --> 34:29.108
- You've got their address.

34:29.192 --> 34:31.152
- I will not have a fugitive
in my house

34:31.235 --> 34:32.695
hiding from her family.

34:34.489 --> 34:35.406
- All right.

34:35.490 --> 34:36.991
- You will make a plan
to see them?

34:37.074 --> 34:38.534
- I'll arrange
to meet my mother.

34:38.618 --> 34:40.244
- I thought you wanted
to avoid them.

34:40.328 --> 34:42.789
- I want to avoid him.

34:42.872 --> 34:45.041
Thank you, Mrs. Van Rhijn.

34:47.293 --> 34:49.670
- Ah, we have a surprise
for you.

34:49.754 --> 34:51.881
It came by hand.

34:56.135 --> 34:58.012
Mrs. Fane is a niece
of my husband,

34:58.096 --> 35:00.598
and Mrs. Morris
was born a Stuyvesant,

35:00.681 --> 35:02.016
so we thought it suitable

35:02.099 --> 35:03.893
for you to begin
your charitable career.

35:03.976 --> 35:06.437
- Training orphans
to be servants?

35:06.521 --> 35:09.482
- To save them
from...something worse.

35:09.565 --> 35:11.275
- There's no need
to go into that.

35:11.359 --> 35:12.944
- But it's addressed to you,
not me.

35:13.027 --> 35:15.696
- They want a donation from us,
but they'll be delighted

35:15.780 --> 35:17.782
when we offer them
a pair of willing hands.

35:17.865 --> 35:19.325
- There'll be
other young women there

35:19.408 --> 35:20.284
your own age.

35:20.368 --> 35:22.161
- And background.

35:22.245 --> 35:23.496
- Very well.

35:36.843 --> 35:38.386
- Are you looking
for your mistress?

35:38.469 --> 35:40.888
- No, no, not especially, sir.

35:40.972 --> 35:43.057
I'm just on my way upstairs.

35:45.643 --> 35:48.521
[soft dramatic music]

35:48.604 --> 35:50.857
♪ ♪

35:50.940 --> 35:54.861
- Tread carefully, Miss Turner.
I speak as a friend.

35:54.944 --> 35:56.821
- You can tread too carefully.

35:56.904 --> 36:01.742
♪ ♪

36:01.826 --> 36:04.745
[soaring orchestral music]

36:04.829 --> 36:11.878
♪ ♪

36:14.839 --> 36:17.842
[indistinct chatter]

36:26.225 --> 36:29.520
- Mr. Russell, have you met
Miss Caroline Astor?

36:29.604 --> 36:30.938
- We've met a few times,

36:31.022 --> 36:32.440
but we don't really
know each other.

36:32.523 --> 36:33.733
- We do now.
- Come on.

36:33.816 --> 36:34.859
You must play something.

36:34.942 --> 36:36.736
- But we're having
such a nice time where we are.

36:36.819 --> 36:38.529
- What makes you think
I brought you here

36:38.613 --> 36:40.281
to have a nice time?

36:40.364 --> 36:42.700
Carrie,
make Mr. Russell play croquet.

36:42.783 --> 36:45.077
Any fool can play croquet.
- But they've started the game.

36:45.161 --> 36:48.748
- Well, barge in
and make them start over.

36:48.831 --> 36:49.749
Mr. Wilson.

36:49.832 --> 36:51.667
- Mrs. Fish is unusual,
isn't she?

36:51.751 --> 36:52.835
- To say the least.

36:52.919 --> 36:54.629
Let's just find some mallets,
and then we can stand

36:54.712 --> 36:57.048
at the edge of the lawn
without attracting attention.

36:58.382 --> 37:00.009
How do you know her?

37:00.092 --> 37:01.469
- Her nephew was
at Harvard with me,

37:01.552 --> 37:04.639
but as to why she took me up,
it's anyone's guess.

37:04.722 --> 37:06.807
- Handsome young men who talk
are always useful.

37:06.891 --> 37:08.476
That's what my mother says.

37:08.559 --> 37:11.062
- And a girl should
always listen to her mother.

37:11.145 --> 37:13.272
- Mr. Van Rhijn,
I thought you weren't coming.

37:13.356 --> 37:15.191
I heard you were in Europe.
- I was.

37:15.274 --> 37:16.317
I've only just got home.

37:16.400 --> 37:18.110
I haven't told anyone
I'm back yet,

37:18.194 --> 37:21.614
but then I thought,
why the devil not?

37:21.697 --> 37:24.450
- May I present Mr. Russell.
- I know how you feel.

37:24.533 --> 37:26.619
I came down from college,
and I left minutes later,

37:26.702 --> 37:27.954
my mother practically calling

37:28.037 --> 37:30.122
down East 61st Street
as I went.

37:30.206 --> 37:31.916
- Where are you on East 61st?

37:31.999 --> 37:34.043
- My parents have built a house
on the corner of Fifth Avenue.

37:34.126 --> 37:35.670
They just moved in.
- But I know it well.

37:35.753 --> 37:37.505
My mother lives
almost opposite.

37:37.588 --> 37:38.506
- Huh.

37:38.589 --> 37:40.007
- Why did they choose
to live so far uptown?

37:40.091 --> 37:41.842
- It's not as far up
as it used to be,

37:41.926 --> 37:43.886
and they wanted a building plot
on the Avenue.

37:43.970 --> 37:45.513
My parents are
Mr. and Mrs. George Russell.

37:45.596 --> 37:46.722
Has your mother spoken of them?

37:46.806 --> 37:50.101
- Yes, but not
as acquaintances.

37:50.184 --> 37:52.186
You've moved in, then.
- I suppose we have.

37:52.269 --> 37:53.229
- We?

37:53.312 --> 37:55.815
- My father, my mother,
and my sister.

37:55.898 --> 37:57.566
- How cozy that sounds.

37:57.650 --> 38:00.528
[plucky orchestral music]

38:00.611 --> 38:03.656
♪ ♪

38:03.739 --> 38:06.742
[indistinct chatter]

38:08.077 --> 38:10.705
- I don't understand
why they have taken you in.

38:10.788 --> 38:13.249
- I did Miss Brook a good turn.

38:13.332 --> 38:15.543
- What sort of good turn?
- It doesn't matter.

38:18.129 --> 38:20.047
- I brought the clothes
as you asked.

38:20.131 --> 38:21.549
- Thank you.

38:23.092 --> 38:24.552
- So what's next?

38:24.635 --> 38:26.595
- I sell an article or a story.

38:26.679 --> 38:29.223
- You know, your father thinks
that will never happen.

38:29.306 --> 38:31.058
- Which is just one
of the many reasons

38:31.142 --> 38:32.727
why I can't come home.

38:32.810 --> 38:35.062
- Eventually,
you have to forgive him.

38:35.146 --> 38:37.648
He was just protecting you.
- From what?

38:37.732 --> 38:39.400
- From a poor choice

38:39.483 --> 38:41.360
that could have
ruined your life.

38:43.821 --> 38:45.698
- Well, I'm back
in New York anyway.

38:45.781 --> 38:49.326
[laughter]

38:49.410 --> 38:51.704
- Why did you choose
this place?

38:51.787 --> 38:52.955
- I like it.

38:54.957 --> 38:56.167
- When will you come home?

38:56.250 --> 38:57.918
- I've told you, I have a job

38:58.002 --> 38:59.211
and the fresh start
that I need.

38:59.295 --> 39:01.047
- You know you get your
stubbornness from your father?

39:01.130 --> 39:02.423
- I don't want
to talk about him.

39:02.506 --> 39:04.425
- He loves you,

39:04.508 --> 39:06.761
and he only wants
the best for you.

39:06.844 --> 39:09.138
- I know he feels
what he thinks is love,

39:09.221 --> 39:10.765
but I disagree
with his definition.

39:10.848 --> 39:12.725
- Maybe he can be hard
and demanding,

39:12.808 --> 39:14.935
but he was only thinking
of your welfare.

39:15.019 --> 39:16.479
I swear.

39:16.562 --> 39:19.106
- But you can't swear
because you weren't there.

39:20.524 --> 39:22.735
- Don't force me to take sides.

39:22.818 --> 39:25.738
[soft dramatic music]

39:25.821 --> 39:28.574
♪ ♪

39:28.657 --> 39:30.409
What are you using for money?

39:30.493 --> 39:32.078
- I don't need money.

39:32.161 --> 39:34.080
I'm fed, I'm paid,
and I have a place to stay.

39:34.163 --> 39:36.624
- Well, I brought you some.
You take it.

39:36.707 --> 39:37.750
- I've told you
I don't need it.

39:37.833 --> 39:39.710
- Don't be silly.
I'm your mother.

39:39.794 --> 39:41.337
I'm allowed to give you money.

39:41.420 --> 39:45.800
♪ ♪

39:45.883 --> 39:47.510
- Thank you.

39:49.720 --> 39:51.055
- I'm going now.

39:53.224 --> 39:56.477
You just remember,
we are all held fast,

39:56.560 --> 39:59.313
frozen in time
until you finally allow us

39:59.396 --> 40:00.981
to move forward.

40:01.065 --> 40:08.030
♪ ♪

40:18.582 --> 40:20.459
- Will there be
anything else, ma'am?

40:20.543 --> 40:22.586
- You tell me.
Will there?

40:22.670 --> 40:24.713
- It might be better
without the broach.

40:24.797 --> 40:26.006
- It's too much?

40:27.675 --> 40:29.510
Yes, it's too much.

40:29.593 --> 40:31.846
[dramatic orchestral music]

40:31.929 --> 40:34.890
Right, that's it.
[sighs]

40:34.974 --> 40:41.939
♪ ♪

41:04.336 --> 41:08.841
- Thank you.
[indistinct chatter]

41:08.924 --> 41:10.885
- Excuse us.

41:10.968 --> 41:13.179
- Mrs. Morris?
- I'm Mrs. Fane.

41:13.262 --> 41:15.598
Mrs. Morris is over there.

41:15.681 --> 41:18.559
- Mrs. Russell,
Mrs. George Russell,

41:18.642 --> 41:20.227
and this is my daughter Gladys.

41:20.311 --> 41:21.520
- Oh.

41:21.604 --> 41:25.691
- From further up Fifth Avenue,
on the corner of 61st Street?

41:25.774 --> 41:27.109
- But of course.

41:27.193 --> 41:31.655
That great--that new house
we've all been talking about.

41:31.739 --> 41:33.240
How good of you to come.

41:33.324 --> 41:36.035
Let me introduce you
to Mrs. Russell, Mrs. Morris.

41:36.118 --> 41:37.661
- How do you do?

41:37.745 --> 41:39.955
- Mrs. Russell has come here
today with her daughter

41:40.039 --> 41:41.874
from their new house
on the corner

41:41.957 --> 41:44.752
of 61st and Fifth.
It's just been finished.

41:44.835 --> 41:46.045
You must know the one I mean.

41:47.338 --> 41:50.049
- How thrilling.
- Who built it for you?

41:50.132 --> 41:51.550
- Our architect
trained in Europe.

41:51.634 --> 41:53.219
Mr. Stanford White.

41:53.302 --> 41:55.429
You must pay us a visit.

41:55.512 --> 41:58.224
- How brave not to go
with the same old builders

41:58.307 --> 41:59.934
everyone else uses.

42:00.017 --> 42:02.478
- I don't think we should
be afraid of new things

42:02.561 --> 42:05.105
or new people.

42:05.189 --> 42:07.524
- How often we have said
to each other,

42:07.608 --> 42:08.734
"We must know the family

42:08.817 --> 42:10.277
who live
in that marvelous house."

42:10.361 --> 42:13.447
Every time we drive past,
and here you are.

42:13.530 --> 42:16.450
I hope we can persuade you
to an interest in our cause.

42:16.533 --> 42:18.369
- As you say, I'm here.

42:18.452 --> 42:20.412
- And you, of course,
Miss Russell.

42:20.496 --> 42:22.081
I trust you'll take our part.

42:22.164 --> 42:24.583
- I certainly intend to.
- My daughter isn't out yet.

42:24.667 --> 42:27.127
She's only here
to accompany me.

42:27.211 --> 42:30.297
- Surely charitable work is
good for the spirit at any age.

42:30.381 --> 42:31.507
- It depends.

42:32.716 --> 42:34.176
- Who's that?

42:34.260 --> 42:37.805
- Oh, Mrs. Chamberlain,
Mrs. Augustus Chamberlain.

42:37.888 --> 42:39.515
- She seems to know
as few people as I do.

42:39.598 --> 42:41.850
- Oh, I think she knows
a good many of the women here.

42:41.934 --> 42:43.477
- They just don't want
to know her.

42:43.560 --> 42:45.145
- Aurora.

42:45.229 --> 42:47.648
- Aunt Ada. You are good.

42:47.731 --> 42:49.942
- Nonsense.
- How is Aunt Agnes?

42:50.025 --> 42:52.820
Is she coming?
- I am her ambassadress.

42:52.903 --> 42:56.115
And this is Miss Marian Brook,
our late brother's daughter.

42:56.198 --> 42:57.825
- How do you do, Miss Brook?

42:57.908 --> 43:00.452
You know, my uncle was married
to your aunt,

43:00.536 --> 43:03.622
and I think we're cousins
anyway through the Livingstons.

43:03.706 --> 43:05.165
Are you in New York for long?

43:05.249 --> 43:07.167
- Marian has come
to live with us,

43:07.251 --> 43:08.961
and she wants to help out
with the charity,

43:09.044 --> 43:10.296
if she can be useful.

43:10.379 --> 43:12.339
- Why, this is manna
from heaven.

43:12.423 --> 43:14.591
I'll send a note
this very afternoon.

43:17.261 --> 43:18.387
I'm so sorry.

43:18.470 --> 43:21.932
Uh, this is Miss Brook,
Miss Marian Brook.

43:24.310 --> 43:26.145
- Mrs. Russell
and Miss Russell.

43:26.228 --> 43:27.980
We are neighbors, I think.

43:28.063 --> 43:29.481
- Of course we are.

43:29.565 --> 43:32.151
- Not that splendid new palace
right on the Avenue.

43:32.234 --> 43:33.694
- The very one.

43:33.777 --> 43:35.487
- I was looking up
at those rows of windows

43:35.571 --> 43:37.656
only this morning wondering
what lies behind them.

43:37.740 --> 43:39.658
- Then you must cross the road
and see.

43:39.742 --> 43:41.618
Isn't that so, Gladys?

43:41.702 --> 43:43.454
- If Miss Brook
could spare the time.

43:43.537 --> 43:45.414
- Of course.

43:45.497 --> 43:47.541
- I think we should go in.

43:47.625 --> 43:50.586
[soft dramatic music]

43:50.669 --> 43:56.717
♪ ♪

43:56.800 --> 43:58.135
- Don't tell Aunt Agnes
they were here.

43:58.218 --> 43:59.720
She'd be livid with me.

43:59.803 --> 44:01.263
- She'll find out.

44:01.347 --> 44:03.390
- I feel rather sorry
for the girl.

44:03.474 --> 44:06.185
- I liked them.
- That's not the point.

44:06.268 --> 44:08.270
- What is the point?
- Let's face it, Aunt Ada.

44:08.354 --> 44:11.357
We need money, and you know
how much those women give

44:11.440 --> 44:13.484
when they want to get in.

44:13.567 --> 44:15.194
- There's a price
for that, Aurora,

44:15.277 --> 44:17.404
and it's no good thinking
you won't have to pay it.

44:17.488 --> 44:23.369
♪ ♪

44:23.452 --> 44:24.828
- Who is that?

44:26.413 --> 44:27.498
- That's Mrs. Chamberlain.

44:30.292 --> 44:32.586
- I don't understand you, sir.

44:32.669 --> 44:35.756
You want to throw money away
just so you can ruin me?

44:35.839 --> 44:37.925
- That's not
how I would put it.

44:38.008 --> 44:39.760
- You intend to build
a new line

44:39.843 --> 44:41.136
right alongside my own

44:41.220 --> 44:43.597
all the way
from Cleveland to Toledo

44:43.680 --> 44:45.599
just to put me out of business.

44:45.682 --> 44:48.769
- I need that stretch,
and I want to control Sandusky.

44:48.852 --> 44:50.646
- Sandusky?

44:50.729 --> 44:54.525
What the hell's Sandusky beyond
a bunch of tents and shanties?

44:54.608 --> 44:56.235
- Sandusky can be
an important city

44:56.318 --> 44:57.820
now the railroad
passes through,

44:57.903 --> 44:59.321
and I want it to be my city.

44:59.405 --> 45:01.865
- Then buy the track
that already exists

45:01.949 --> 45:04.076
and save yourself thousands.

45:04.159 --> 45:07.079
- But you turned me down,
twice.

45:07.162 --> 45:08.372
- I turned down your offer

45:08.455 --> 45:10.457
because I thought
you'd come back with more.

45:10.541 --> 45:12.793
It's called negotiation.

45:12.876 --> 45:14.711
- Not in my book, Mr. Thorburn.

45:14.795 --> 45:16.630
You refused my bid,

45:16.713 --> 45:19.550
and now I will build a new line
alongside yours.

45:19.633 --> 45:22.344
- Which would wipe me out.

45:22.428 --> 45:24.471
- I'm afraid that'll be
a consequence, yes,

45:24.555 --> 45:26.598
but it is not
my principal intention.

45:26.682 --> 45:28.475
- Oh, isn't it?

45:28.559 --> 45:30.894
Well, thank the Lord.

45:30.978 --> 45:32.688
- Is there anything else?

45:32.771 --> 45:34.773
Because I have
another appointment.

45:34.857 --> 45:36.108
- So what you are saying is,

45:36.191 --> 45:37.609
you would rather
waste a fortune

45:37.693 --> 45:40.946
than pay an honest price
for a line already operating?

45:41.029 --> 45:43.282
- But I do not see it
as a waste.

45:43.365 --> 45:44.700
Once people learn
that my second offer

45:44.783 --> 45:45.909
is invariably my last,

45:45.993 --> 45:47.870
they won't, as a rule,
refuse me.

45:47.953 --> 45:50.289
Over the years, I expect
to save a lot more money

45:50.372 --> 45:52.124
than I am spending now.

45:52.207 --> 45:53.834
- You bastard.

45:55.586 --> 45:58.338
- I may be a bastard,
Mr. Thorburn,

45:58.422 --> 46:00.340
but you are a fool,

46:00.424 --> 46:04.011
and of the two,
I think I know which I prefer.

46:06.472 --> 46:08.390
Now, good day to you, sir.

46:08.474 --> 46:15.022
♪ ♪

46:22.237 --> 46:24.114
- Do you often come
to Newport, Miss Astor?

46:24.198 --> 46:25.282
- I will.

46:25.365 --> 46:27.618
My parents bought a house here
last year, Beechwood.

46:27.701 --> 46:29.161
They've nearly finished
the renovations,

46:29.244 --> 46:30.412
so I suppose
I'll be here a lot.

46:30.496 --> 46:32.664
- Oh, was there much to do
to the place?

46:32.748 --> 46:34.500
- Well, obviously, my mother
couldn't live in a house

46:34.583 --> 46:36.210
without a ballroom.
- [chuckles]

46:36.293 --> 46:37.211
You may laugh,

46:37.294 --> 46:39.797
but as my mother
never tires of pointing out,

46:39.880 --> 46:41.089
our future success in New York

46:41.173 --> 46:44.218
depends entirely on the support
and approval of Mrs. Astor.

46:44.301 --> 46:45.719
- Mm.
- I'm afraid it's true.

46:45.802 --> 46:48.722
She is quite a force.
- A force for good, I hope.

46:48.805 --> 46:51.725
- Well, a force
to be reckoned with.

46:51.808 --> 46:53.101
- The butler
was looking for you.

46:53.185 --> 46:55.729
- Ah, he found me.
He had a letter from my mother.

46:55.812 --> 46:57.773
She wrote that a cousin
has come to live with them

46:57.856 --> 47:00.192
while I've been away,
Miss Marian Brook.

47:00.275 --> 47:01.193
- Mm.

47:01.276 --> 47:02.736
- So that is something
to look forward to.

47:02.819 --> 47:04.655
A dumpy spinster
with a face like a cabbage

47:04.738 --> 47:06.573
and a figure to match.

47:06.657 --> 47:08.659
- [claps]

47:08.742 --> 47:10.452
We're going into dinner,
but before we do,

47:10.536 --> 47:12.704
I want to warn you
that when you return,

47:12.788 --> 47:14.331
you will find
tables have been set up

47:14.414 --> 47:16.917
for the game of Cinch,
and you are all playing.

47:17.000 --> 47:20.087
- But suppose
we don't know how.

47:20.170 --> 47:21.713
- Then you will learn
during dinner.

47:21.797 --> 47:23.757
[laughter]

47:23.840 --> 47:26.134
- Cinch? Do we really have to?

47:26.218 --> 47:28.428
- I'd say there's no escape.

47:28.512 --> 47:30.389
- [laughs]

47:34.685 --> 47:37.729
[knocks at door]

47:37.813 --> 47:42.401
- I'm so sorry that got torn.
- It wasn't your fault.

47:42.484 --> 47:45.153
- How was your excursion?
- So-so.

47:45.237 --> 47:48.615
At least she brought me
some of my clothes.

47:48.699 --> 47:50.742
- What are the staff here like?

47:50.826 --> 47:55.414
- Nice on the whole,
with one or two exceptions.

47:55.497 --> 47:56.415
- [chuckles]

47:56.498 --> 47:58.208
I ought to go down
and say hello.

47:58.292 --> 47:59.835
- Marian?

47:59.918 --> 48:01.587
- Ah.

48:02.879 --> 48:04.798
- Marian.

48:04.881 --> 48:06.925
- I've decided
to give an at home.

48:07.009 --> 48:09.136
- And what does that mean?
- You know perfectly well.

48:09.219 --> 48:11.305
I'll send cards saying
we'll receive after dinner

48:11.388 --> 48:14.308
on such and such an evening,
and they're welcome to look in.

48:14.391 --> 48:15.475
- Who are they?

48:15.559 --> 48:16.518
- Mrs. Fane was telling me

48:16.602 --> 48:18.312
how curious people are
about the house.

48:18.395 --> 48:19.688
- They want our money, Bertha.

48:19.771 --> 48:22.065
- It's a good cause.
- I'm sure.

48:22.149 --> 48:23.400
And I'm glad
if you'd like to donate,

48:23.483 --> 48:24.651
but please
don't deceive yourself

48:24.735 --> 48:26.236
that their interest in us
is something more.

48:26.320 --> 48:28.071
- George, we have
to start somewhere.

48:28.155 --> 48:29.865
Everyone calls
on Mrs. Vanderbilt now.

48:29.948 --> 48:30.907
They're seen everywhere.

48:30.991 --> 48:32.159
- What's that
got to do with it?

48:32.242 --> 48:33.702
- When his grandfather
arrived in New York,

48:33.785 --> 48:34.786
no one would go near him.

48:34.870 --> 48:37.122
- That was half a century ago.
What are you saying?

48:37.205 --> 48:38.457
We have to keep this up
for 50 years,

48:38.540 --> 48:39.791
and then someone may drop by?

48:39.875 --> 48:42.336
- Things move faster nowadays.
- That's a relief.

48:42.419 --> 48:43.962
- I think what father means
is that we--

48:44.046 --> 48:45.172
- They want to see this house.

48:45.255 --> 48:46.131
They've watched it going up,

48:46.214 --> 48:47.507
and now they'd like
to see inside.

48:47.591 --> 48:48.842
- It doesn't make them
your friends.

48:48.925 --> 48:51.511
- I'm not asking them
to dine or dance.

48:51.595 --> 48:52.721
I won't use the ballroom.

48:52.804 --> 48:54.264
I'll save that
for another time.

48:54.348 --> 48:56.016
I just want them to look in,
and I don't think

48:56.099 --> 48:57.309
they'll be able to resist.

48:57.392 --> 48:59.019
Church, please tell Mrs. Bruce.

48:59.102 --> 49:00.687
- Yes, ma'am.

49:00.771 --> 49:02.022
- Is it true Miss Ada
and Miss Marian

49:02.105 --> 49:03.982
met Mrs. Russell
from across the road

49:04.066 --> 49:05.233
at that charity event?

49:05.317 --> 49:06.318
- How do you know that?

49:06.401 --> 49:07.819
- I saw one of their footmen
in the street,

49:07.903 --> 49:10.030
and he was talking about it.

49:10.113 --> 49:11.239
Miss Armstrong?

49:11.323 --> 49:12.366
- I don't think I should say.

49:12.449 --> 49:14.326
- Don't tell me you're having
a fit of discretion,

49:14.409 --> 49:15.494
Miss Armstrong.

49:15.577 --> 49:17.663
- I don't understand.
Why does it matter?

49:17.746 --> 49:20.457
- It'll matter when
Mrs. Van Rhijn hears about it.

49:20.540 --> 49:22.209
- Oh, she'll have to give in
one day.

49:22.292 --> 49:23.585
- Why?

49:23.669 --> 49:25.045
- Well, because they own
the future,

49:25.128 --> 49:26.588
men like Mr. Russell,

49:26.672 --> 49:28.715
and Mrs. Van Rhijn will have
to come to terms with it

49:28.799 --> 49:30.550
sooner or later,
stands to reason.

49:30.634 --> 49:31.802
- What will you do
if she doesn't?

49:31.885 --> 49:35.180
- Me?
Nothing, I guess.

49:35.263 --> 49:36.306
- Oh, I see.

49:36.390 --> 49:38.100
You spoke so definitely,
I thought you had

49:38.183 --> 49:40.727
some course of action
planned in protest.

49:40.811 --> 49:44.189
- No, Mr. Bannister.
- No, and don't you forget it.

49:46.108 --> 49:48.527
- But what is the scale
of this at home to be?

49:48.610 --> 49:50.696
- You can talk it through
with the mistress tomorrow.

49:50.779 --> 49:53.198
- If they come, it will
only be out of curiosity

49:53.281 --> 49:54.241
to see the house.

49:54.324 --> 49:55.617
- What makes you say that?

49:55.701 --> 49:57.703
- The master is successful,
isn't he?

49:57.786 --> 50:00.414
People want to know you
when you're a success.

50:00.497 --> 50:03.000
It's when you fail
they turn their backs.

50:03.083 --> 50:05.085
- You sound rather bitter,
Mr. Watson.

50:05.168 --> 50:06.795
- Oh, just stating the fact.

50:06.878 --> 50:08.880
- Are you keeping
something from us?

50:08.964 --> 50:10.590
- No.
- Come, Miss Turner.

50:10.674 --> 50:12.384
There is no need
to put him on the spot.

50:12.467 --> 50:14.052
- I don't need protection,
Mrs. Bruce,

50:14.136 --> 50:15.303
thank you.

50:15.387 --> 50:16.638
I've nothing to hide.

50:16.722 --> 50:18.306
- Well, if that is true,

50:18.390 --> 50:20.726
you must be
a very unusual person.

50:23.311 --> 50:26.106
[spirited orchestral music]

50:26.189 --> 50:33.196
♪ ♪

50:35.991 --> 50:38.994
[dog barking]

50:48.086 --> 50:49.087
- Welcome home, Mr. Larry.

50:49.171 --> 50:50.255
I hope you had
a pleasant journey.

50:50.338 --> 50:52.466
- Yes, thank you.
It was very nice.

50:52.549 --> 50:54.801
[dog barking]

50:54.885 --> 50:56.303
- Pumpkin!
Come back here!

50:56.386 --> 50:57.345
Pumpkin!

50:58.513 --> 51:00.599
- Whoa!

51:00.682 --> 51:02.225
[horse neighs]
Get out of the way!

51:03.727 --> 51:05.353
- Good heavens, that was brave.

51:05.437 --> 51:06.938
- Anyone would have
done the same.

51:07.022 --> 51:08.148
- I doubt it,

51:08.231 --> 51:10.400
or there'd be bodies
up and down Fifth Avenue.

51:10.484 --> 51:11.777
- [chuckles]

51:11.860 --> 51:14.404
Are you a Van Rhijn?
- Almost.

51:14.488 --> 51:17.491
Mrs. Van Rhijn is my aunt.
I'm Marian Brook.

51:17.574 --> 51:20.577
- Oscar van Rhijn's cousin?
- Yes.

51:20.660 --> 51:23.789
- Oh, you're not
as he described you.

51:23.872 --> 51:25.791
Uh, I'm Larry Russell.

51:25.874 --> 51:27.209
- Ah.

51:27.292 --> 51:28.668
- Well, you'd better tell them

51:28.752 --> 51:30.629
to keep him under control
in future.

51:30.712 --> 51:32.839
- Nobody can keep Pumpkin
under control,

51:32.923 --> 51:34.841
not for very long anyway.

51:34.925 --> 51:38.178
- Miss Brook.
- Mr. Russell.

51:38.261 --> 51:41.139
[soaring orchestral music]

51:41.223 --> 51:42.808
♪ ♪

51:42.891 --> 51:45.060
[chuckles]

51:45.143 --> 51:47.187
♪ ♪

51:47.270 --> 51:49.815
- Thank you, Church.
There's a good man.

51:49.898 --> 51:51.650
Has my trunk arrived
from college?

51:51.733 --> 51:54.361
- It has, and it's
been unpacked, Mr. Larry.

51:54.444 --> 51:57.489
- Hello, there.
How is everything?

51:57.572 --> 51:59.324
- Much as usual,

51:59.407 --> 52:02.160
except that Mother has decided
to give her first soirée.

52:02.244 --> 52:03.620
- There you are, dear.

52:03.703 --> 52:06.998
Have you had a lovely time?
- Lovely enough.

52:07.082 --> 52:08.125
- You should have
your own valet

52:08.208 --> 52:09.292
now you're down from Harvard.

52:09.376 --> 52:10.877
It's not fair to burden Church.

52:10.961 --> 52:13.171
- I gather we are going
to christen the new house.

52:13.255 --> 52:15.382
- Just a few people calling in,
but I think it's time.

52:15.465 --> 52:16.716
- How many are coming?

52:16.800 --> 52:18.093
- It's hard to say
if they don't accept

52:18.176 --> 52:19.678
in a formal way,
but I think if we cater

52:19.761 --> 52:21.596
for 200, it's probably safe.

52:21.680 --> 52:22.722
- Wow.

52:22.806 --> 52:25.225
- I thought you'd like to ask
some friends of yours.

52:25.308 --> 52:26.268
- Such as?

52:26.351 --> 52:27.978
- Such as Mrs. Fish
or the Goelets

52:28.061 --> 52:29.354
or that nice Miss Astor.

52:29.437 --> 52:30.564
- I hardly know them.

52:30.647 --> 52:32.566
I was only there
to make up numbers.

52:32.649 --> 52:34.401
Are you inviting
Mrs. Van Rhijn?

52:34.484 --> 52:36.152
- Maybe.
Now go and wash.

52:36.236 --> 52:38.363
We'll have luncheon
in a minute.

52:38.446 --> 52:41.491
[spirited orchestral music]

52:41.575 --> 52:48.540
♪ ♪

52:48.623 --> 52:50.083
[dog barking]

52:50.166 --> 52:52.294
- Why do you bring
that beastly dog?

52:52.377 --> 52:55.046
Dogs are supposed to run
alongside carriages,

52:55.130 --> 52:56.423
not travel in them.

52:56.506 --> 52:59.759
- Oh, I think we must make
an exception for Pumpkin.

52:59.843 --> 53:03.179
- I've asked Oscar for tea.
It's time he met you.

53:03.263 --> 53:05.932
He'll have a friend with him,
John Adams.

53:06.016 --> 53:07.350
- That's nice.

53:07.434 --> 53:09.936
- This John is Quincy Adams'
great-grandson.

53:10.020 --> 53:11.646
You will call him Mr. Adams,

53:11.730 --> 53:14.107
and wear
one of your new dresses.

53:14.190 --> 53:15.734
- I almost forgot.

53:15.817 --> 53:17.569
Bannister gave me this
as I was leaving.

53:17.652 --> 53:19.613
A footman left it
just before we came down.

53:19.696 --> 53:21.656
- It's from Mrs. Russell.

53:21.740 --> 53:23.909
It's addressed to you,
as well, Marian.

53:23.992 --> 53:27.746
Mrs. Van Rhijn, Miss Brook,
Miss Marian Brook.

53:27.829 --> 53:29.581
- She's clearly had lessons
in etiquette.

53:29.664 --> 53:31.082
- She's trying
to be neighborly.

53:31.166 --> 53:34.669
- It's an invitation.
- Addressed to us?

53:34.753 --> 53:37.339
- They were bound
to entertain soon.

53:37.422 --> 53:38.798
They can't have built
that great house

53:38.882 --> 53:40.508
to sit by the fire and read.

53:40.592 --> 53:42.761
- Well, let them entertain
their own sort.

53:42.844 --> 53:44.846
Heaven knows there are plenty
to choose from.

53:46.389 --> 53:47.974
- Aunt Agnes,
I have a question.

53:48.058 --> 53:50.143
Who is
Mrs. Augustus Chamberlain?

53:51.728 --> 53:53.647
- Where have you heard
that name?

53:53.730 --> 53:56.608
- Mrs. Chamberlain was at
Mrs. Fane's charity gathering.

53:56.691 --> 53:59.611
- Was she, by heavens?
Ada, who else was there?

53:59.694 --> 54:01.947
Pickpockets?
Newly released criminals?

54:02.030 --> 54:04.115
What was Aurora thinking?

54:04.199 --> 54:07.285
- One must remember
that the point of the exercise

54:07.369 --> 54:08.745
is to raise money.

54:08.828 --> 54:10.830
- That is no excuse
for risking the reputation

54:10.914 --> 54:12.624
of every lady in the room.

54:12.707 --> 54:16.002
Marian, when and if you see
Mrs. Chamberlain again,

54:16.086 --> 54:17.587
you are to turn your face away.

54:17.671 --> 54:21.091
Is that clear?
- Very.

54:21.174 --> 54:23.885
So what about
Mrs. Russell's party?

54:23.969 --> 54:27.138
I presume we're not going.
- Are you mad?

54:27.222 --> 54:33.019
♪ ♪

54:33.103 --> 54:34.688
- Would you please see
that Mrs. Morris...

54:34.771 --> 54:35.730
That Mrs. Fane...

54:35.814 --> 54:37.107
That Mrs. Astor gets this?

54:38.233 --> 54:40.485
I'm afraid Mrs. Fish
is not at home, madam.

54:40.568 --> 54:41.695
- Really?

54:41.778 --> 54:43.738
Only she knows my son,
Larry Russell.

54:43.822 --> 54:46.366
He was just staying with her
in Newport.

54:46.449 --> 54:48.326
- She's not at home, madam.

54:48.410 --> 54:52.580
- But you'll give her my card
and this envelope?

54:52.664 --> 54:55.000
You'll say I called?
- Of course, madam.

54:55.083 --> 55:02.090
♪ ♪

55:18.732 --> 55:21.151
- Thank you, gentlemen.
That's all.

55:21.234 --> 55:24.195
[indistinct chatter]

55:25.905 --> 55:27.699
Tell Atkins no.

55:27.782 --> 55:31.036
Warn Schultz I'm interested,
but not yet convinced.

55:31.119 --> 55:32.412
Give Brennan till 10:00
tomorrow morning,

55:32.495 --> 55:34.039
or the deal's off.
- Very good.

55:34.122 --> 55:35.707
- Mr. Stanford White
is outside.

55:35.790 --> 55:37.042
- Oh, bring him in.
Bring him in.

55:37.125 --> 55:38.585
Thank you, Clay.

55:41.504 --> 55:43.757
Mr. White,
sorry to drag you here

55:43.840 --> 55:45.633
when no doubt
you've had a busy day.

55:45.717 --> 55:47.010
- I hope nothing's wrong
with the house.

55:47.093 --> 55:49.763
- Oh, quite the contrary.
It's working splendidly.

55:49.846 --> 55:52.474
So splendidly, in fact,
that Mrs. Russell has decided

55:52.557 --> 55:54.642
it is time we began
to entertain.

55:54.726 --> 55:56.603
- That's what it was built for.

55:56.686 --> 55:58.438
- You will receive a card
from her.

55:58.521 --> 56:01.149
She feels our guests will be
interested in the place.

56:01.232 --> 56:03.568
She'd like you there
to answer questions.

56:03.651 --> 56:05.070
- I should be honored,
of course.

56:06.863 --> 56:08.656
- I hope it's a success.

56:08.740 --> 56:11.034
- Well, people are curious
about the house,

56:11.117 --> 56:12.452
they want your money
for pet causes,

56:12.535 --> 56:14.412
and your children
are both good-looking.

56:14.496 --> 56:16.081
I'd say it will be.

56:16.164 --> 56:18.708
- Can you help her, Mr. White?

56:18.792 --> 56:21.461
- How?
I'm not fashionable.

56:21.544 --> 56:23.171
But I'm glad to be able
to thank you properly

56:23.254 --> 56:24.881
for taking a chance on me.

56:24.964 --> 56:27.008
- You have Mrs. Russell
to thank, not me.

56:27.092 --> 56:29.928
Whatever her faults, she has
imagination and taste...

56:30.011 --> 56:32.639
- Oh.
- And nerve.

56:32.722 --> 56:34.724
- She will need all three
in New York.

56:39.562 --> 56:41.064
- I've left them
for you to sign.

56:41.147 --> 56:42.982
- Thank you, Miss Scott.
- Hello, Mother.

56:43.066 --> 56:44.609
The wanderer has returned.

56:44.692 --> 56:46.945
- You took your time
coming to tell me.

56:47.028 --> 56:49.781
This is Miss Scott
who is helping with my post.

56:49.864 --> 56:52.492
My son, Mr. Van Rhijn.
- Hello.

56:52.575 --> 56:53.993
- I'll leave you.

56:57.664 --> 56:59.833
- Look at her work.

56:59.916 --> 57:01.960
Where's Mr. Adams?
- I'm meeting him here.

57:02.043 --> 57:03.670
Why did you want me
to bring him?

57:03.753 --> 57:04.879
- You should have come earlier.

57:04.963 --> 57:06.172
You've been home for ages,

57:06.256 --> 57:07.715
and you've never even met
your cousin.

57:07.799 --> 57:09.968
- Well, I'm here now.

57:10.051 --> 57:12.220
How long will she be staying?
- Why?

57:12.303 --> 57:14.514
- Well, I'll already have
Aunt Ada around my neck,

57:14.597 --> 57:17.016
that's if anything
should happen to you.

57:17.100 --> 57:19.519
- Why must you always
sound so sharp?

57:19.602 --> 57:21.020
- I presume
I'm expected to keep

57:21.104 --> 57:22.438
the house running indefinitely.

57:22.522 --> 57:23.982
- I shouldn't worry
about Marian.

57:24.065 --> 57:25.859
She'll be gone
long before I am.

57:25.942 --> 57:28.736
- What makes you so sure?
- Marian, my dear.

57:30.363 --> 57:33.199
I don't believe you have
ever met my son, Oscar.

57:33.283 --> 57:34.492
- Mr. Van Rhijn,

57:34.576 --> 57:36.703
I was beginning to think
you were only a dream.

57:36.786 --> 57:38.913
- Should we kiss?
We are cousins.

57:38.997 --> 57:41.040
- Let's shake hands for now.

57:41.124 --> 57:43.334
- But I hope
you'll call me Oscar.

57:43.418 --> 57:44.711
- He's been in Europe.

57:44.794 --> 57:47.046
- I know. How I envy you.

57:47.130 --> 57:49.549
- It was mostly dull meetings
and dusty boardrooms.

57:49.632 --> 57:52.010
- Oh, I can't believe that.
- Mr. Adams.

57:53.553 --> 57:55.597
- Mr. Adams, how good of you
to drop by.

57:55.680 --> 57:57.307
What can we give you?
- Nothing.

57:57.390 --> 57:59.392
Thank you, Mrs. Van Rhijn.

57:59.475 --> 58:02.562
- May I present Mr. Adams,
my dear.

58:02.645 --> 58:04.314
Miss Marian Brook is my niece.

58:04.397 --> 58:06.357
She has just arrived
in the city.

58:06.441 --> 58:08.401
- Is it your first visit
to New York?

58:08.484 --> 58:11.112
- It's my first visit
to almost anywhere.

58:11.196 --> 58:13.198
Can you help me
with what I should see?

58:13.281 --> 58:14.365
- I'm sure Mrs. Van Rhijn
will have

58:14.449 --> 58:16.784
a comprehensive list
of museums.

58:18.286 --> 58:20.997
- So the Russells have moved
into their house in my absence.

58:21.080 --> 58:22.081
- Don't remind me.

58:22.165 --> 58:23.750
- I ran into the son
in Newport.

58:23.833 --> 58:26.211
He's nice enough, and I gather
there's a daughter.

58:26.294 --> 58:28.922
- I believe so.
- I should like to meet her.

58:29.005 --> 58:31.090
Are you going to their soirée?
- Of course not.

58:31.174 --> 58:33.593
Don't say such things.
- Mama, you are incorrigible.

58:33.676 --> 58:35.845
- I take that
as the highest praise.

58:37.764 --> 58:39.390
- I need four more pallets.

58:41.100 --> 58:43.478
- Rice stacked.
I'll be right back.

58:43.561 --> 58:44.479
This way.

58:44.562 --> 58:51.527
♪ ♪

58:55.198 --> 58:57.200
- She said 200,
but I must be ready

58:57.283 --> 59:00.620
with more at a moment's notice
if we go over that figure.

59:00.703 --> 59:01.788
- So what's wrong?

59:01.871 --> 59:04.290
- I'm not making
ham sandwiches.

59:04.374 --> 59:05.917
I'm not making toast.

59:06.000 --> 59:08.795
- I sympathize, monsieur,
but we have our orders.

59:08.878 --> 59:11.464
- Madam does not understand how
these things should be managed.

59:11.547 --> 59:13.800
- Ooh.
- I beg your pardon?

59:13.883 --> 59:16.302
- You know as well as I do
she isn't one of them.

59:16.386 --> 59:18.846
I used to work
for Mrs. Griswold on 50th.

59:18.930 --> 59:20.306
That's why Madam hired me,

59:20.390 --> 59:22.684
to teach her the ways
of the old people,

59:22.767 --> 59:25.144
but Mrs. Griswold wouldn't
have come near this house.

59:25.228 --> 59:27.146
- Then she was
a very stupid woman.

59:27.230 --> 59:29.440
- The mistress is not a player
in the great game,

59:29.524 --> 59:30.692
whatever she says.

59:30.775 --> 59:33.528
- Well, Miss Turner, I hope
you can overcome your distaste

59:33.611 --> 59:34.779
and give the mistress
a helping hand

59:34.862 --> 59:36.531
with her clothes
for the evening.

59:40.034 --> 59:41.577
- Surely things are changing.

59:41.661 --> 59:44.664
- Not fast enough
for Mrs. Russell.

59:44.747 --> 59:46.624
- You always act
as if you liked her.

59:46.708 --> 59:48.626
- When I have to.

59:48.710 --> 59:50.837
She does not have the manner
of the real people,

59:50.920 --> 59:52.338
and she cannot learn it.

59:52.422 --> 59:54.674
Mrs. Griswold would see
through her in a moment,

59:54.757 --> 59:56.509
in just a moment.

59:56.592 --> 59:59.304
- If she was so wonderful,
why did you leave?

59:59.387 --> 1:00:02.181
Or were you fired?

1:00:02.265 --> 1:00:04.976
- She died, Mr. Watson,
of a heart attack

1:00:05.059 --> 1:00:07.520
just as she was changing
for Mrs. Astor's ball.

1:00:07.603 --> 1:00:09.939
It was very hard
on Mr. Griswold.

1:00:10.023 --> 1:00:11.482
- Because he was left
all alone.

1:00:11.566 --> 1:00:13.985
- Because he wanted
to go to the ball.

1:00:16.070 --> 1:00:18.656
[door clicks]

1:00:18.740 --> 1:00:21.909
- Oh, you're almost ready.
I should get changed.

1:00:21.993 --> 1:00:22.994
- There's no hurry.

1:00:23.077 --> 1:00:24.370
I just want to be downstairs
to supervise

1:00:24.454 --> 1:00:26.831
all the final details.

1:00:26.914 --> 1:00:29.125
Oh, it feels as if
it's held on with nails.

1:00:29.208 --> 1:00:30.418
- You look superb.

1:00:32.754 --> 1:00:34.297
So...

1:00:34.380 --> 1:00:36.466
are you ready
for your trial by hospitality?

1:00:36.549 --> 1:00:40.386
- Well, if I'm not ready now,
I never will be.

1:00:40.470 --> 1:00:42.388
- What was it
your mother used to say?

1:00:42.472 --> 1:00:44.015
"You are the only one
of my children

1:00:44.098 --> 1:00:45.391
who is worthy of my dreams"?

1:00:45.475 --> 1:00:47.643
- Much good
did those dreams do her.

1:00:47.727 --> 1:00:50.396
She had nothing while she lived
and nothing when she died.

1:00:50.480 --> 1:00:52.398
- You loved her.

1:00:52.482 --> 1:00:55.818
That wasn't nothing.
- Thank you.

1:00:55.902 --> 1:00:57.945
- Don't you think she'd be
proud of you this evening?

1:00:58.029 --> 1:01:00.907
- I wonder.
Ask me again at midnight.

1:01:00.990 --> 1:01:03.701
- I wish you'd invited
some of the old crowd.

1:01:03.785 --> 1:01:05.036
The house will be
full of strangers.

1:01:05.119 --> 1:01:07.330
- We're headed in a different
direction now, George.

1:01:07.413 --> 1:01:09.082
We're joining a different club.
- Mm.

1:01:09.165 --> 1:01:10.666
Even if they don't want us
to be members?

1:01:10.750 --> 1:01:12.251
- Why shouldn't we be members?

1:01:12.335 --> 1:01:15.046
I'm tired of letting
all those dull and stupid women

1:01:15.129 --> 1:01:17.090
dictate the way
we live our lives.

1:01:17.173 --> 1:01:19.092
Why, you've done more
for this city in ten years

1:01:19.175 --> 1:01:21.052
than their families
have achieved in centuries.

1:01:21.135 --> 1:01:22.178
- Things are changing, Bertha.

1:01:22.261 --> 1:01:23.930
- They can't change
fast enough for me.

1:01:24.013 --> 1:01:25.890
- And you've come a long way.

1:01:25.973 --> 1:01:27.600
Even I can see that.

1:01:27.683 --> 1:01:30.770
- I don't want to come
a long way.

1:01:30.853 --> 1:01:33.898
I want to go all the way.

1:01:33.981 --> 1:01:37.068
- I'd just like you
to be happy.

1:01:37.151 --> 1:01:40.113
And I know my loving you
is not enough.

1:01:40.196 --> 1:01:41.656
- It's almost enough.

1:01:47.870 --> 1:01:49.622
- I should go.
- Mm.

1:01:49.705 --> 1:01:51.374
- Watson will be wondering
where I am.

1:01:51.457 --> 1:01:54.460
[spirited orchestral music]

1:01:54.544 --> 1:02:01.509
♪ ♪

1:02:11.394 --> 1:02:13.688
- Quite a spectacle, isn't it?

1:02:13.771 --> 1:02:16.232
- Well, they sure are taking
a lot of trouble.

1:02:17.900 --> 1:02:20.570
- It must seem hard
to miss the party,

1:02:20.653 --> 1:02:22.447
but Agnes feels
so very strongly.

1:02:22.530 --> 1:02:25.199
- She can't make me
dislike them.

1:02:25.283 --> 1:02:27.660
- Nor would she want to.
- Yes, she would.

1:02:29.704 --> 1:02:31.706
- Well, perhaps she would,
but I would not.

1:02:36.085 --> 1:02:39.046
I'll see you downstairs.

1:02:39.130 --> 1:02:40.465
[sighs]

1:02:40.548 --> 1:02:42.508
You mustn't think harshly
of Agnes.

1:02:42.592 --> 1:02:44.385
Her life has not
always been easy.

1:02:44.469 --> 1:02:47.763
- Why did she hate
my father so?

1:02:47.847 --> 1:02:49.974
- He sold our family farms.

1:02:50.057 --> 1:02:51.601
He sold the house
where we were born

1:02:51.684 --> 1:02:54.687
and where we had lived
for a century and a half.

1:02:54.770 --> 1:02:56.689
And then he just spent
the money.

1:02:56.772 --> 1:02:58.691
He bought nothing.
He saved nothing.

1:02:58.774 --> 1:03:01.068
He gave us,
his sisters, nothing.

1:03:01.152 --> 1:03:03.571
- So she felt
he'd betrayed you both.

1:03:03.654 --> 1:03:05.907
- That's how it was for her.

1:03:05.990 --> 1:03:08.618
You see, our father had
died quite young,

1:03:08.701 --> 1:03:11.829
and we depended
on Henry entirely.

1:03:11.913 --> 1:03:13.456
- So she wasn't
already married?

1:03:13.539 --> 1:03:16.209
- No, but he'd proposed,
and so she felt

1:03:16.292 --> 1:03:18.544
she had no choice.

1:03:18.628 --> 1:03:21.756
Henry had let us down,
and there was nothing for it

1:03:21.839 --> 1:03:23.883
but to marry Mr. Van Rhijn.

1:03:23.966 --> 1:03:25.843
- And he was not an easy man.

1:03:28.763 --> 1:03:29.889
- He was not a man

1:03:29.972 --> 1:03:32.099
you would like
to be alone with.

1:03:36.521 --> 1:03:39.023
All I ask is that
you give us a chance.

1:03:39.106 --> 1:03:42.568
We are not as Henry
described us to you.

1:03:42.652 --> 1:03:45.196
Please...

1:03:45.279 --> 1:03:46.864
just give us a chance.

1:03:56.791 --> 1:03:58.709
- Is everything
ready downstairs?

1:03:58.793 --> 1:04:00.586
- They're all
rather excited, sir.

1:04:00.670 --> 1:04:02.630
Been waiting to entertain
on a grand scale

1:04:02.713 --> 1:04:03.923
since we got here.

1:04:05.508 --> 1:04:08.094
- As long as we are
entertaining on a grand scale.

1:04:08.177 --> 1:04:13.099
♪ ♪

1:04:13.182 --> 1:04:14.600
- Take out the chrysanthemums.

1:04:14.684 --> 1:04:16.435
I said specifically,
"No chrysanthemums."

1:04:16.519 --> 1:04:17.645
- Yes, ma'am.

1:04:17.728 --> 1:04:19.564
- When are they laying
the carpet across the sidewalk?

1:04:19.647 --> 1:04:21.065
- They're doing it now, madam.

1:04:21.148 --> 1:04:23.734
- And Monsieur Baudin
isn't too hysterical?

1:04:23.818 --> 1:04:26.654
- Well...
- We should start dinner.

1:04:30.032 --> 1:04:32.243
- Why don't you look in?

1:04:32.326 --> 1:04:34.078
You needn't stay for long.

1:04:34.161 --> 1:04:35.997
- Aunt Agnes would have a fit.

1:04:37.790 --> 1:04:39.000
- Does she have to know?

1:04:40.459 --> 1:04:41.335
I could wait downstairs

1:04:41.419 --> 1:04:42.878
to make sure
you can get back in.

1:04:45.256 --> 1:04:47.550
- My fellow conspirator.

1:04:50.761 --> 1:04:52.305
- We must let them get in here.

1:04:52.388 --> 1:04:55.099
They need to clear away
and start laying the supper.

1:04:55.182 --> 1:04:57.643
- No cigars and brandy
for you, Father.

1:04:57.727 --> 1:04:59.770
- We could go
to the smoking room.

1:04:59.854 --> 1:05:01.230
- Is there anything
I can do, Mother?

1:05:01.314 --> 1:05:03.274
- Go to bed.
- She's not a child.

1:05:03.357 --> 1:05:05.401
- So you keep telling me.

1:05:05.484 --> 1:05:07.612
- Well, no one will mind
that she isn't officially out,

1:05:07.695 --> 1:05:08.946
not in her own mother's house.

1:05:09.030 --> 1:05:11.282
- Why isn't she out, anyway?
She ought to be.

1:05:11.365 --> 1:05:12.908
She should have made
her debut this year.

1:05:12.992 --> 1:05:14.910
- I wish to present her
at a ball in this house,

1:05:14.994 --> 1:05:16.912
and I'm not giving one until
I know we can fill the rooms.

1:05:16.996 --> 1:05:18.831
- Let he stay, my dear.
- [sighs]

1:05:18.914 --> 1:05:20.124
If you're all
going to bully me--

1:05:20.207 --> 1:05:21.751
- I can help.

1:05:21.834 --> 1:05:24.837
- Oh, very well.
Go and get changed.

1:05:24.920 --> 1:05:27.381
Church, tell them to come in.
- Very good, ma'am.

1:05:27.465 --> 1:05:34.472
♪ ♪

1:05:38.434 --> 1:05:40.061
- I think I may go up
and lie down.

1:05:40.144 --> 1:05:41.687
I've got rather a headache.

1:05:41.771 --> 1:05:43.314
- What about an early night?

1:05:43.397 --> 1:05:45.191
- I'll see.
You wouldn't mind?

1:05:45.274 --> 1:05:46.901
- Not at all.

1:05:52.406 --> 1:05:54.950
[door clicks]

1:05:55.034 --> 1:05:56.535
- Where's Marian?

1:05:56.619 --> 1:05:59.121
- She's gone upstairs.
She has a headache.

1:05:59.205 --> 1:06:02.583
She was asking earlier
why you disliked Henry so.

1:06:04.210 --> 1:06:05.419
- Did you tell her?

1:06:05.503 --> 1:06:08.714
- I did, but I tried
not to make it too vivid.

1:06:08.798 --> 1:06:10.966
- She can be
so like him at times.

1:06:12.510 --> 1:06:15.012
She speaks
and I hear Henry's voice,

1:06:15.096 --> 1:06:17.515
challenging everything
just as he did.

1:06:18.974 --> 1:06:21.060
And look how that turned out.

1:06:21.143 --> 1:06:23.396
- Well, I like
her strong views.

1:06:23.479 --> 1:06:25.314
I like her energy.

1:06:26.440 --> 1:06:29.026
Don't worry, Agnes,
she's clever.

1:06:29.110 --> 1:06:32.029
She'll learn the rules.
- Will she?

1:06:32.113 --> 1:06:34.365
Revolutions are launched
by clever people

1:06:34.448 --> 1:06:37.702
with strong views
and excess energy.

1:06:37.785 --> 1:06:40.871
[dog barking]

1:06:40.955 --> 1:06:47.962
♪ ♪

1:07:05.187 --> 1:07:06.689
[horse neighs]

1:07:06.772 --> 1:07:13.738
♪ ♪

1:07:17.324 --> 1:07:20.619
- Thank you.
- Miss Brook, welcome.

1:07:20.703 --> 1:07:22.329
If you'll come this way.

1:07:28.377 --> 1:07:29.754
Miss Brook.
- Ah.

1:07:29.837 --> 1:07:31.964
- Miss Brook,
what a nice surprise.

1:07:32.047 --> 1:07:33.674
Are your aunts with you?

1:07:33.758 --> 1:07:35.926
- I'm afraid
they couldn't get away.

1:07:36.010 --> 1:07:38.137
- But you are made
of sterner stuff.

1:07:38.220 --> 1:07:39.597
Ah, Larry.

1:07:39.680 --> 1:07:41.140
May I present my son,
Larry Russell.

1:07:41.223 --> 1:07:42.641
Miss Marian Brook.
You're neighbors.

1:07:42.725 --> 1:07:43.642
You should know each other.

1:07:43.726 --> 1:07:45.102
- Mrs. Fane.
- Oh, yes, thank you.

1:07:45.186 --> 1:07:46.312
- Excuse me.

1:07:50.232 --> 1:07:52.943
- I hope the little dog
recovered from its shock.

1:07:53.027 --> 1:07:54.779
- His near demise, you mean.

1:07:54.862 --> 1:07:56.906
Don't worry.
He's very resilient.

1:08:00.493 --> 1:08:03.788
I guess I'm a bit early.
- I don't think so.

1:08:03.871 --> 1:08:05.623
You see, Miss Brook,
my father's dollars

1:08:05.706 --> 1:08:08.167
do not always have
the desired effect.

1:08:08.250 --> 1:08:10.211
Usually, but not always.

1:08:10.294 --> 1:08:12.379
- You don't seem to mind much.
- I don't.

1:08:12.463 --> 1:08:14.673
These things
should happen naturally.

1:08:14.757 --> 1:08:16.550
Unlike my dear mother,
I'm not a big believer

1:08:16.634 --> 1:08:17.885
in forcing change.

1:08:17.968 --> 1:08:20.638
- Then I suspect she and I
have more in common than we do.

1:08:20.721 --> 1:08:21.847
[chuckles]

1:08:21.931 --> 1:08:24.183
- How are you enjoying
living with your aunts?

1:08:24.266 --> 1:08:26.519
- They've taken me in,
so I should be grateful,

1:08:26.602 --> 1:08:28.229
but we seem to disagree
on so many topics

1:08:28.312 --> 1:08:30.648
that I'm sure we'll come
to blows in the end.

1:08:30.731 --> 1:08:32.983
- Perhaps they'll educate you,
you'll educate them,

1:08:33.067 --> 1:08:34.819
and you'll meet
somewhere in the middle.

1:08:34.902 --> 1:08:37.488
- Hello, Miss Brook.
- Hello, Miss Russell.

1:08:37.571 --> 1:08:38.489
- Have you met?

1:08:38.572 --> 1:08:41.408
- Yes, but you mustn't
tell my aunt.

1:08:41.492 --> 1:08:43.035
- Is Mr. Fane not with you?

1:08:43.118 --> 1:08:44.829
- He wanted to be very much,

1:08:44.912 --> 1:08:47.122
but business has tied him
to his desk.

1:08:47.206 --> 1:08:49.708
- And Mrs. Morris, she was
so curious about the house.

1:08:49.792 --> 1:08:51.377
- How she longed to come.

1:08:51.460 --> 1:08:53.170
- But she couldn't
get away either?

1:08:53.254 --> 1:08:54.547
- Isn't it a shame?

1:08:54.630 --> 1:08:56.173
- A real shame when you think

1:08:56.257 --> 1:08:58.551
of the check
you both want from me.

1:08:58.634 --> 1:09:00.594
- I know, but I thought
if I came alone

1:09:00.678 --> 1:09:03.889
and just stayed a few minutes,
then that might...

1:09:03.973 --> 1:09:04.890
I mean--

1:09:04.974 --> 1:09:07.434
- I know what you mean,
Mrs. Fane.

1:09:07.518 --> 1:09:09.061
And please don't feel
you have to linger.

1:09:09.144 --> 1:09:10.187
It's really not necessary.

1:09:12.940 --> 1:09:15.276
Just go, Mrs. Fane.

1:09:15.359 --> 1:09:16.694
Please go.

1:09:16.777 --> 1:09:19.697
[soft dramatic music]

1:09:19.780 --> 1:09:25.703
♪ ♪

1:09:25.786 --> 1:09:28.914
- I wonder if I might ask you
for a carriage across town.

1:09:28.998 --> 1:09:30.374
- Yes, of course, madam.
Right away.

1:09:30.457 --> 1:09:31.584
- She wasn't here long.

1:09:31.667 --> 1:09:34.086
I suppose Mother's made
another quarrel.

1:09:34.170 --> 1:09:36.589
- I'm afraid
I can't stay either.

1:09:36.672 --> 1:09:38.924
I just wanted to look in to pay
my respects to your parents.

1:09:39.008 --> 1:09:41.760
- I hope we can meet again.
- I'm sure we will.

1:09:41.844 --> 1:09:43.637
- Let the three of us
be friends

1:09:43.721 --> 1:09:45.431
in spite of everything.

1:09:45.514 --> 1:09:46.891
Contra mundum.

1:09:52.479 --> 1:09:53.898
- Leaving already, Miss Brook?

1:09:53.981 --> 1:09:56.692
- I'm afraid I must get back,
but thank you for including me.

1:09:56.775 --> 1:09:58.903
- For including you in what?

1:09:58.986 --> 1:10:00.988
- Thank you for coming,
Miss Brook.

1:10:04.116 --> 1:10:05.242
- Who was that?

1:10:05.326 --> 1:10:07.745
- Our neighbor,
Miss Marian Brook.

1:10:07.828 --> 1:10:09.914
And there's no need
to be angry with her, my dear.

1:10:09.997 --> 1:10:11.582
The aunts will have
forbidden her to come,

1:10:11.665 --> 1:10:13.417
and she has chosen
to defy them.

1:10:13.500 --> 1:10:16.795
- But why must I be the enemy?
- Well, that's easy.

1:10:16.879 --> 1:10:18.839
They have been in charge
since the "Mayflower" landed,

1:10:18.923 --> 1:10:22.843
and now it's your turn,
because you are the future,

1:10:22.927 --> 1:10:25.304
and if you are the future,
then they must be the past.

1:10:25.387 --> 1:10:27.473
That's what frightens them.

1:10:27.556 --> 1:10:34.188
♪ ♪

1:10:34.271 --> 1:10:36.815
- Miss Brook?
What are you doing here?

1:10:36.899 --> 1:10:39.985
Does Aunt Agnes know?
- No.

1:10:40.069 --> 1:10:43.280
And please don't give me away.
- I won't tell if you don't.

1:10:43.364 --> 1:10:44.490
Good night.

1:10:44.573 --> 1:10:48.285
I hope we meet again soon
in less foreign climes.

1:10:48.369 --> 1:10:51.288
[spirited orchestral music]

1:10:51.372 --> 1:10:58.379
♪ ♪

1:11:01.590 --> 1:11:03.092
[door clicks]

1:11:28.283 --> 1:11:29.410
- Oh.

1:11:30.577 --> 1:11:32.705
I was just going up
to check on you.

1:11:32.788 --> 1:11:34.540
How is the headache?
- Much better.

1:11:34.623 --> 1:11:36.917
Quite gone, in fact.
- I'm glad.

1:11:37.001 --> 1:11:39.044
- We should go up.

1:11:39.128 --> 1:11:40.379
Come along, Ada.

1:11:40.462 --> 1:11:42.715
It's long past your bedtime.

1:11:42.798 --> 1:11:46.218
By the way, we have decided
to make you a modest allowance.

1:11:46.301 --> 1:11:49.972
It won't be much, but you'll
have a little independence.

1:11:50.055 --> 1:11:52.349
- But you've already given me
so many clothes.

1:11:52.433 --> 1:11:55.102
- Fiddle-faddle.
No nonsense, please.

1:11:59.106 --> 1:12:01.191
- I don't deserve it, truly,

1:12:01.275 --> 1:12:05.195
as I cannot promise to live
within Aunt Agnes' confines.

1:12:05.279 --> 1:12:06.488
- I understand.

1:12:08.449 --> 1:12:10.367
I only ask

1:12:10.451 --> 1:12:13.537
that you never break
your own moral code,

1:12:13.620 --> 1:12:17.166
for that is the soundest guide
any of us can have.

1:12:19.335 --> 1:12:21.170
- How wise, Aunt Ada.

1:12:23.005 --> 1:12:25.424
- Please don't sound
quite so surprised.

1:12:25.507 --> 1:12:27.926
[soft dramatic music]

1:12:28.010 --> 1:12:30.220
[horse whinnies]

1:12:30.304 --> 1:12:37.269
♪ ♪

1:13:00.000 --> 1:13:02.961
- What will you do with it all?

1:13:03.045 --> 1:13:05.297
- Church, get the kitchen staff
to box it up

1:13:05.380 --> 1:13:06.548
and send a message
in the morning

1:13:06.632 --> 1:13:08.133
to the Charity
Organization Society.

1:13:08.217 --> 1:13:09.843
Ask them to collect it.

1:13:09.927 --> 1:13:11.386
- I don't know
what the poor of New York

1:13:11.470 --> 1:13:13.514
will make of lobster salad.

1:13:13.597 --> 1:13:18.477
♪ ♪

1:13:18.560 --> 1:13:21.897
Thank you, Church.

1:13:21.980 --> 1:13:24.149
- Well, then, take it away.

1:13:28.695 --> 1:13:32.491
- Cooking for paupers,
that's not what I'm used to.

1:13:32.574 --> 1:13:34.284
- I dare say you're not used
to making supper

1:13:34.368 --> 1:13:36.328
for guests who never turn up.

1:13:36.411 --> 1:13:39.790
- The evening was a folly.
This house is a folly.

1:13:39.873 --> 1:13:41.792
She's built a palace
to entertain the sort of people

1:13:41.875 --> 1:13:43.168
who will never come here.

1:13:43.252 --> 1:13:44.837
- Don't count her out
so quickly.

1:13:44.920 --> 1:13:47.339
- I agree.
She knows what she wants.

1:13:47.422 --> 1:13:48.757
Why shouldn't she try
to get it?

1:13:48.841 --> 1:13:51.135
- It's nothing to me
if she fails or succeeds.

1:13:51.218 --> 1:13:53.804
- Isn't it, Miss Turner?
You seem to take it personally.

1:13:53.887 --> 1:13:56.306
- Failure's catchable,
Mr. Church.

1:13:56.390 --> 1:13:58.350
It rubs off
if you're not careful.

1:13:58.433 --> 1:14:00.936
- And what about Mr. Russell?

1:14:01.019 --> 1:14:03.522
Is he a failure too?

1:14:03.605 --> 1:14:10.529
♪ ♪

1:14:10.612 --> 1:14:11.864
- I'll accept her payment,

1:14:11.947 --> 1:14:14.199
and I'll stay for as long
as she wants me to.

1:14:14.283 --> 1:14:15.993
I need the work,

1:14:16.076 --> 1:14:18.495
and besides,
it will leave me time to write.

1:14:18.579 --> 1:14:19.705
- Write what?

1:14:19.788 --> 1:14:22.541
- Short stories, articles,

1:14:22.624 --> 1:14:24.751
and I hope one day
to write a novel.

1:14:26.170 --> 1:14:27.421
- How ambitious.

1:14:27.504 --> 1:14:29.715
- Some may
think it far-fetched.

1:14:29.798 --> 1:14:30.841
My father does.

1:14:30.924 --> 1:14:33.552
- But women have been
successful writers for years.

1:14:33.635 --> 1:14:37.556
- White women,
but I have a few precedents.

1:14:37.639 --> 1:14:41.393
- Then why shouldn't you?
I envy you.

1:14:42.853 --> 1:14:45.480
I'd like to work too, properly.

1:14:45.564 --> 1:14:47.566
- What at?

1:14:47.649 --> 1:14:48.734
- I'm not like you.

1:14:48.817 --> 1:14:51.653
I don't have any burning talent
yearning to be free.

1:14:51.737 --> 1:14:55.157
I just want to be busy,
to be needed,

1:14:55.240 --> 1:14:57.034
to be in a hurry.

1:14:57.117 --> 1:14:59.036
- You know
they'd never allow it,

1:14:59.119 --> 1:15:00.412
except for charity.

1:15:00.496 --> 1:15:01.830
- Then I'll work
at my charities

1:15:01.914 --> 1:15:03.290
and wait to see what comes.

1:15:05.125 --> 1:15:07.127
After all, we've made it
to this city.

1:15:07.211 --> 1:15:09.922
- That's right.
You're a New Yorker now.

1:15:10.005 --> 1:15:11.673
We both are,

1:15:11.757 --> 1:15:14.218
and for a New Yorker,
anything is possible.

1:15:15.761 --> 1:15:20.140
So good luck to both of us,
and good night.

1:15:23.185 --> 1:15:24.436
- Good night, Peggy.

1:15:24.519 --> 1:15:27.439
[spirited orchestral music]

1:15:27.522 --> 1:15:34.488
♪ ♪

1:16:04.893 --> 1:16:07.354
- How was your evening?

1:16:07.437 --> 1:16:08.939
- Wasted.

1:16:09.022 --> 1:16:11.608
I wanted to go to a party.

1:16:11.692 --> 1:16:15.112
- Any party?
- No, the Russells' party.

1:16:16.738 --> 1:16:19.449
I wasn't invited.
- You will be next time.

1:16:21.118 --> 1:16:24.329
What was the attraction?

1:16:24.413 --> 1:16:27.249
- Never mind about that now.

1:16:27.332 --> 1:16:34.339
♪ ♪

1:17:03.785 --> 1:17:05.787
- Good evening,
Mr. and Mrs. Roosevelt.

1:17:05.871 --> 1:17:07.164
- Good evening, Hefty.

1:17:07.247 --> 1:17:09.791
- Good evening, Miss Caroline.
- Good evening, Hefty.

1:17:09.875 --> 1:17:13.587
♪ ♪

1:17:13.670 --> 1:17:15.422
Is Mrs. Astor
still awake, Hefty?

1:17:15.505 --> 1:17:16.715
- She's in the drawing room.

1:17:16.798 --> 1:17:18.258
- Say good night to Mama
for me.

1:17:18.342 --> 1:17:21.094
I'm nearly dead,
and Rosy has to be up at dawn.

1:17:21.178 --> 1:17:23.305
- I will.

1:17:23.388 --> 1:17:25.807
- Good night.
- Good night, Carrie.

1:17:27.309 --> 1:17:30.562
- Hello, Mother.
- Carrie, dear.

1:17:30.645 --> 1:17:33.148
How was it?
- All right.

1:17:33.231 --> 1:17:34.983
Mr. Dvorák played
until I thought

1:17:35.067 --> 1:17:37.027
his fingers would fall off,

1:17:37.110 --> 1:17:38.320
and then he spoke
about composing,

1:17:38.403 --> 1:17:39.863
and we couldn't
understand a word.

1:17:39.946 --> 1:17:42.199
- Where's Helen?
- She's gone to bed.

1:17:42.282 --> 1:17:44.493
Rosy has to get up early
for some diplomatic thing.

1:17:44.576 --> 1:17:46.078
- I wish you wouldn't
call him that.

1:17:46.161 --> 1:17:47.871
- I can't call him
Mr. Roosevelt.

1:17:47.954 --> 1:17:50.791
- Call him James.
- Nobody calls him James.

1:17:52.250 --> 1:17:55.295
What are these?
- Old invitations.

1:17:55.379 --> 1:17:56.421
I was looking through them

1:17:56.505 --> 1:17:59.341
to see if I needed to keep
any of the addresses.

1:17:59.424 --> 1:18:01.259
- This one was for tonight.

1:18:01.343 --> 1:18:04.262
Mrs. George Russell
at 1801 Fifth Avenue.

1:18:04.346 --> 1:18:05.597
- Are you awake?

1:18:05.680 --> 1:18:08.642
[soft dramatic music]

1:18:08.725 --> 1:18:12.646
♪ ♪

1:18:12.729 --> 1:18:14.272
Would you like me
to come in with you?

1:18:30.414 --> 1:18:33.041
This is harder
than you thought it would be.

1:18:33.125 --> 1:18:35.419
I know that.

1:18:35.502 --> 1:18:36.878
But I hope you won't give up.

1:18:42.592 --> 1:18:44.761
Good night.

1:18:44.845 --> 1:18:47.597
- I met their son in Newport
with Mamie Fish.

1:18:49.933 --> 1:18:52.811
Did you go?
- Don't be ridiculous.

1:18:54.438 --> 1:18:55.647
- I'll never give up!

1:18:57.065 --> 1:19:00.444
And I promise you this.
I'll make them sorry one day.

1:19:00.527 --> 1:19:02.487
- I'm glad to hear it, my dear.

1:19:02.571 --> 1:19:04.114
Defeat is not your color.

1:19:04.197 --> 1:19:07.159
[dramatic orchestral music]

1:19:07.242 --> 1:19:12.956
♪ ♪

1:19:13.039 --> 1:19:16.001
[breathing heavily]

1:19:16.084 --> 1:19:23.049
♪ ♪

1:20:42.671 --> 1:20:44.631
[bright tone]
